{"title_page": "Woody Allen sexual assault allegation", "text_new": "{{short description|Dylan Farrow's accusations of Woody Allen sexually abusing her}}\nIn August 1992, the American film director [[Woody Allen]] was accused by his adoptive daughter Dylan Farrow, then 7 years old, of having sexually molested her in the home of her adoptive mother, the actress [[Mia Farrow]], in [[Bridgewater, Connecticut]].<ref name=OrthNov1992/> Allen has repeatedly denied the allegation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/woody-allen-defends-himself-on-60-minutes-in-92/|title=Woody Allen defends himself on '60 Minutes' in '92|publisher=[[CBS News]]|accessdate= February 8, 2018|archivedate=November 22, 2014| archiveurl=https://archive.is/VNhj0|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=AllenFeb72014/>\n\nWhen the allegation was made, Mia Farrow and Allen had been in a 12-year relationship and had three children together: two adopted children, Dylan and Moses, and one biological son, Satchel (now known as [[Ronan Farrow]]).<ref name=OrthNov1992/> The molestation is alleged to have taken place eight months after Farrow learned that Allen had been having an affair with another of her adoptive daughters, [[Soon-Yi Previn]], who married Allen in 1997; Previn was a first-year undergraduate and 21 years old when Farrow found out about the relationship.<ref name=Wypijewski26Feb2014/> Allen alleged that the affair prompted Mia Farrow to concoct the molestation allegation as an act of vengeance.<ref name=AllenFeb72014/> The Connecticut [[State's Attorney]] investigated the allegation but did not press charges,<ref name=Henneberger25Sept1993/> the Connecticut State Police referred Dylan to the Child\nSexual Abuse Clinic of\u00a0Yale\u2013New\u00a0Haven Hospital who concluded that Woody Allen had not sexually abused Dylan<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> and the New York Department of Social Services found \"no credible evidence\" to support the allegation.<ref name=PerezPena26Oct1993/> In response to the allegation, Allen sued Farrow for sole custody of Dylan, Satchel and Moses.<ref name=Weber14Aug1992/> He lost the case in June 1993; the judge concluded that the allegation of sexual abuse had not been proven.<ref name=\":0\">{{citation |first=Elliott|last= Wilk|publisher=Supreme Court: New York County |title=Custody Court Ruling}}</ref> Visitations with Dylan were suspended for six months until the girl recovered from what she had suffered so far,<ref>{{citation |first=Elliott|last= Wilk|publisher=Supreme Court: New York County  |title=Custody Case Ruling |date=July 6, 1993}}</ref> gave him limited, supervised visitation with Satchel, and allowed Moses, a teenager, to decide for himself.<ref name=Marks8June1993/><ref name=Shea7Feb2014/> The decision was upheld on appeal in 1994<ref name=appeal1994/> and 1995.<ref name=appeal1995/>\n\nDylan Farrow has repeated the allegation several times as an adult, although with important modifications with respect to the original narration of 1992 as it was described by Mia Farrow.<ref>{{Cite book|title=What Falls Away : A Memoir|first=Mia|last=Farrow|isbn=9781984800114|pages=299|oclc=1035846541|date=2018-05-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/dylan-farrow-interview-today-gayle-king-full-transcript-woody-allen-me-too/|title=Dylan Farrow details her sexual molestation allegations against Woody Allen|last=January 18|first=CBS News|last2=2018|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-22|last3=Am|first3=7:20}}</ref> Her first public comment was in an interview with [[Maureen Orth]] for ''Vanity Fair'' in 2013,<ref name=OrthOct2013/> followed by an open letter in the<!--CMOS 8.170--> ''New York Times'' in 2014,<ref name=Farrow1Feb2014/> and a ''Los Angeles Times'' [[op-ed]] in December 2017.<ref name=Farrow7Dec2017/> Woody Allen has also spoken publicly about the allegations, in an interview with [[Gayle King]] for ''[[CBS This Morning]]'', in  a ''New York Times'' op-ed<ref name=AllenFeb72014/> and in 2018 with a statement to CBS \u2013 each time denying the allegation.<ref name=CBS2018re>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/woody-allen-responds-dylan-farrow-sexual-abuse-allegations/|title=Woody responds to Dylan Farrow sexual abuse allegations|date=January 18, 2018|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n===Allen and Farrow===\nWoody Allen and Mia Farrow began a 12-year relationship in 1980, during which Farrow starred in 13 of Allen's films.<ref name=OrthOct2013>{{cite news|url= https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2013/11/mia-farrow-frank-sinatra-ronan-farrow| title=Momma Mia!| first=Maureen|last=Orth|author-link=Maureen Orth|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]| date= October 23, 2013}}</ref> They maintained separate apartments in [[Manhattan]] throughout the relationship\u2014Farrow on [[Central Park West]]<ref name=Smith8May1994/> and Allen on [[Fifth Avenue]]\u2014and did not marry; they had both been married twice.<ref name=Lax24Feb1991/>\n\n[[File:Mia Farrow 2012 Shankbone.JPG|thumb|upright|[[Mia Farrow]], 2012]]\nWhen the relationship began, Farrow had seven children: three biological sons from her marriage to composer [[Andr\u00e9 Previn]]; three adopted girls (two Vietnamese and one Korean, [[Soon-Yi Previn]]); and one adopted Korean boy, Moses.<ref name=Lax24Feb1991>{{cite news | title=Woody and Mia: A New York Story |first=Eric|last=Lax|work=The New York Times|date=February 24, 1991|url= https://www.nytimes.com/1991/02/24/magazine/woody-and-mia-a-new-york-story.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Woody Allen, Mia Farrow family tree|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/02/03/showbiz/gallery/allen-farrow-family-tree/index.html|publisher=CNN|date=May 11, 2016}}</ref> In July 1985 she adopted a baby girl, Dylan, from Texas. Allen was not involved in the adoption, but when Dylan arrived he assumed a parental role toward her and began spending more time in Farrow's home. He and Farrow went on holiday to Europe several times with the Farrow\u2013Previn children between 1987 and 1989, although the judicial investigation concluded that \"He remained aloof from Ms. Farrow's other children except for Moses, to whom he was cordial.\"<ref name=Stern10Feb2014>{{cite news|last1=Stern|first1=Marlow|title=Inside the Shocking Custody Case Court Documents that Shed Light on the Dylan Farrow-Woody Allen Saga|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/inside-the-shocking-custody-case-court-documents-that-shed-light-on-the-dylan-farrow-woody-allen-saga|work=The Daily Beast|date=February 10, 2014}}</ref> In December 1987 Farrow gave birth to Allen's biological son, Satchel (later known as [[Ronan Farrow]]).<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1987/12/22/arts/son-born-to-mia-farrow-and-woody-allen.html | title = Son Born to Mia Farrow And Woody Allen | agency = Associated Press |newspaper=The New York Times | date= December 22, 1987}}</ref> Farrow wanted to adopt another child in 1991; Allen said he would not take \"a lousy attitude toward it\" so long as she agreed to his adoption of Dylan and Moses,<ref name=Stern10Feb2014/> and in October that year she adopted another Vietnamese child.{{efn|Farrow found that the child was too disabled and needed more care than she could provide; she helped to find him another family.<ref name=Smith8May1994>{{cite news|last1=Dinitia|first1=Smith|title=Picking Up The Legos And The Pieces|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/02/23/reviews/farrow-feature.html|work=The New York Times|date=May 8, 1994}}</ref>}} Allen's adoption of Dylan and Moses was finalized on December 17, 1991.<ref name=Stern10Feb2014/>\n\n{{external media\n| float  = left\n| width  = 230px\n| image1 = [https://web.archive.org/web/20180122001118/https://imagesvc.timeincapp.com/v3/mm/image?url=http%3A%2F%2Fpeoplev6.alley.ws%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2016%2F08%2Fwoody-allen-01-600.jpg On holiday, Leningrad, 1987]<br/>''Left to right'': [[Ronan Farrow|Ronan]], Lark, Woody Allen, Dylan, Fletcher, Daisy, [[Soon-Yi Previn]], Moses, and Mia Farrow.\n| image2 = [http://images.nymag.com/news/features/scandals/scandals120409_1992_560.jpg Allen, Farrow and Soon-Yi Previn], c.&nbsp;1987.\n}}\nAccording to her testimony during the custody trial, Farrow became concerned about Allen's behavior around Dylan in 1987\u20131988. She reportedly told Allen that he was paying too much attention to Dylan and failing to give her \"breathing room\". He had allegedly read to Dylan while in his underwear, allowed her to suck his thumb, and would sit on her bed in the morning waiting for her to wake up.<ref name=Stern10Feb2014/><ref name=Marks27March1993/><ref name=OrthNov1992/> Farrow would later testify that she found Allen's relationship with Dylan at this time \"relentless and overpowering\", and said it had \"a wooing quality\";<ref name=\"wmr\">[https://www.upi.com/Archives/1993/03/25/Mia-I-worried-about-Woody-being-a-homosexual/8544733035600/ \"Mia: I worried about Woody being a homosexual\"]. William M. Reilly, March 25, 1993. [[UPI.com]]. Retrieved 14 October 2018.</ref> however, in 1990 Mia Farrow changed her will so that in the event of her death the care and custody of her minor children (Dylan, Satchel and Moses) would be left to Allen.<ref>{{Cite book|title=What Falls Away:a memoir|last=Farrow|first=Mia|publisher=Doubleday|year=1997|isbn=0-385-47187-4|location=New York|pages=249 }}</ref> Furthermore, in 1991, she made an affidavit to the judge promoting the adoption of Dylan and Moses by Allen, praising especially the qualities of Allen as Dylan's father: \"Mr. Allen is a loving, caring, attentive parent to Dylan and she can only benefit from having him as an adoptive father\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1993/01/12/More-bombshells-dropped-at-Woody-Allen-hearing/8879726814800/|title=More bombshells dropped at Woody Allen hearing|last=REILLY|first=M. William|date=Jan 12, 1993|website=UPI Archives|access-date=}}</ref> Farrow also told her therapist that she feared Woody \"would abuse Satchel\", and that she also worried that Allen had a sexual relationship \"with another man\".<ref name=\"wmr\" /> On one occasion, Dylan allegedly locked herself in the bathroom for four hours when he arrived; Allen had an employee pick the lock with a coat hanger.<ref name=Marks27March1993/> The family psychologist, Dr. Susan Coates, witnessed some of Allen's behavior and testified during the custody trial in 1993 that she did not see it as sexual, but as \"inappropriately intense because it excluded everybody else\".<ref name=Wypijewski26Feb2014/><ref name=Marks30March1993/> Allen said later that he had paid extra attention to Dylan to compensate for the time Farrow was spending with the newborn, Satchel.<ref name=appeal1994/> According to Maureen Orth, he agreed in 1990 to discuss the issue in therapy sessions;<ref name=OrthNov1992/> however, the therapist Dr. Coates, stated at the trial that Woody Allen was not in therapy with her and that both parents were part of the children's therapy. Woody Allen wanted to improve as a father, but he was not in therapy for inappropriate behaviors with Dylan.<ref>{{cite web |last1=L. Miller |first1=Tracy |title=Psychiatrist: Woody was committed to being a good father |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1993/03/30/Psychiatrist-Woody-was-committed-to-being-a-good-father/1405733467600/ |website=UPI |access-date=March 30, 1990}}</ref>\n\n===Relationship with Previn===\nIn 1991 Allen began an affair with Farrow's adopted daughter Soon-Yi Previn. According to Allen, it began in late December 1991.<ref name=PerezPena23March1993/> In August 1992 Mia Farrow told her lawyer, Alan Dershowitz, that Soon Yi had acknowledged by talking to her that the relationship between Allen and Soon Yi had begun on December 1, 1991.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=NEW YORK DAILY NEWS Easter Season Poll, 1986|last=Hackett|first=Larry|date=1988-06-01|page=5|doi = 10.3886/icpsr08584}}</ref> Later she said it began while Previn was in her final year of high school, which ended in June 1991. She alleged that Dylan saw Allen and Previn on the bed together in the summer or autumn of 1991.<ref name=Marks27March1993>{{cite news|last1=Marks|first1=Peter|title=Farrow Says Daughter Became Distraught Over Allen's Relentless Attention|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/02/23/reviews/farrow-trial.html|work=The New York Times|date=March 27, 1993}}</ref> The appeal Court Ruling found that the sexual relationship between Allen and Soon Yi began in December 1991.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Appellate Division of the Supreme Court of the State of New York, First Department. |title=Woody Allen, Appellant, v. Maria V. Farrow, Also Known as Mia Farrow, Respondent |date=May 12, 1994 |volume=197 A.D.2d 327 (1994) }}</ref> One point of contention has been how old Previn was at the time. When Farrow and Andr\u00e9 Previn adopted her from [[Seoul]] in 1977, the Seoul family court gave her a legal birth document  with a presumptive birth date of October 8, 1970; she had been abandoned and was living in that city's St. Paul's Orphanage.{{efn|\"Information concerning this case was obtained from Mr. and Mrs. Andr\u00e9 G. Previn&nbsp;... The beneficiary, Soon Hee Oh, aka Soon Yi Oh, is a native and citizen of Korea with a presumptive birth date of October 8, 1970.\"<ref>United States Congressional Serial Set, Issue 13173, 1977, p.&nbsp;[https://books.google.com/books?id=1TYoAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Soon+Hee+Oh,+aka+Soon+Yi+Oh%22 170].</ref> \"Memorandum of information concerning H.R. 1352 for the relief of Oh Soon Hee submitted by the American Embassy at Seoul, Korea. The beneficiary is an abandoned child, who was found in Seoul, Korea on February 12, 1976. She was placed temporarily in the care of Maria's House, a local institution for abandoned children while an effort was made to identify and locate her parents and relatives. When this search failed, the beneficiary was transferred to the care of St. Paul's Orphanage&nbsp;... in Seoul, where she currently lives. The Seoul Family Court established a Family Census Register (legal birth document) in her behalf on December 28, 1976, with a presumptive birth date of October 8, 1970. The beneficiary attends kindergarten classes held in the orphanage. Through the auspices of the Social Welfare Society, Inc.,&nbsp;... and the Friends of Children adoption agency in the United States, the child has been selected for adoption by Mr. and Mrs. Andr\u00e9 George Previn, of Martha's Vineyard, Mass.&nbsp;...<ref>United States Congressional Serial Set, 1978, p.&nbsp;[https://books.google.com/books?id=UPBIAQAAMAAJ&dq=%22Soon-Yi%22+Previn+%22October+8%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22October+8%22 cxlii\u2013cxliv].</ref>}} According to Farrow, the family regarded her date of birth as October 8, 1972,<ref name=Wypijewski26Feb2014/> although the first reaction of the nanny Kristi Groteke when in May 1992 Mia Farrow told her that Woody Allen had had a relationship with Soon Yi was to remember that she was a 21-year-old woman.<ref>{{cite book|title=Mia & Woody. Love and betrayal|last1=Groteke|first1=Kristi|last2=Rosen|first2=Marjorie|publisher=Carroll & Graf Publishers, Inc.|year=1994|isbn=0-7867-0066-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/miawoodylovebetr00grot/page/79 79]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/miawoodylovebetr00grot/page/79}}</ref> The timing of the affair became an issue in part because Farrow attempted, unsuccessfully, to have Allen's adoption of Dylan and Moses declared void after the molestation allegation, on the grounds that his affair with Previn had begun before the adoptions were finalized on December 17, 1991.<ref name=Perez19June1993/>\n\n[[File:Soon Yi Previn and Woody Allen at the Tribeca Film Festival.jpg|thumb|left|[[Soon-Yi Previn]] and [[Woody Allen]], 2009]]\nDuring her final year of high school, Previn told Allen that she wanted to be a model; he advised her how to dress and arranged for professional photographs to be taken.<ref name=OrthNov1992/> She reportedly asked if she could accompany him to a basketball game, and after attending several together, they became closer.<ref name=Isaacson31Aug1992>{{cite news|last1=Isaacson|first1=Walter|title=The Heart Wants What It Wants|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,160439,00.html|work=Time|date=June 24, 2001|at=First published August 31, 1992}}</ref><ref name=Stern10Feb2014/> Their affair came to light on January 13, 1992, when Farrow found nude [[Instant camera|Polaroid]] photographs of Previn on the [[Fireplace mantel|mantel]] in Allen's home.<ref name=Wypijewski26Feb2014/><ref name=Perez20March1993/> Previn was by then in her first year at [[Drew University]] in New Jersey.<ref name=OrthNov1992/> Allen, then 56, told Farrow that he had taken the photographs the day before, and that he and Previn had first had sex in the last week of December 1991.<ref name=PerezPena23March1993>{{cite news|last1=Perez-Pena|first1=Richard|title=Nude Photographs Are Focus Of Woody Allen's Testimony|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/03/23/nyregion/nude-photographs-are-focus-of-woody-allen-s-testimony.html|work=The New York Times|date=March 23, 1993}}</ref><ref name=Perez19June1993/> Allen told the custody trial in 1993 that he regarded the images as erotic, but not pornographic; the appellate court said that it did not \"share Mr. Allen's characterization\" of the photographs.<ref name=appeal1994/>\n\nAlthough the discovery shocked the family, Farrow did not stop Allen from visiting her home,<ref name=OrthOct2013/> and she completed her work on ''[[Husbands and Wives]]'' (1992), the last film of his in which she appeared.<ref name=Grimes31Aug1992>{{cite news|last1=Grimes|first1=William|title=A Chronology of a Film's Making And a Relationship's Unmaking|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/08/31/movies/a-chronology-of-a-film-s-making-and-a-relationship-s-unmaking.html|work=The New York Times|date=August 31, 1992}}</ref><ref name=Barron21Aug1992>{{cite news|last1=Barron|first1=James|title=Plot of New Woody Allen Film Seems to Mimic His Life|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/08/21/nyregion/plot-of-new-woody-allen-film-seems-to-mimic-his-life.html|work=The New York Times|date=August 21, 1992}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=James|first1=Caryn|title=Film View; And Here We Thought We Knew Him|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/09/06/movies/film-view-and-here-we-thought-we-knew-him.html|work=The New York Times|date=September 6, 1992}}</ref> According to Farrow, Allen said his relationship with Previn was over;<ref name=OrthOct2013/> she alleged that Allen asked her to issue a joint press release, in response to rumors about the relationship, in which she would confirm there was nothing between Allen and Previn, but she refused to do it.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Farrow|first1=Mia|title=What Falls Away|date=1997|publisher=Bantam|location=New York|page=269|ref=harv}}</ref> She was hurt and angry,<ref name=Marks30March1993/> but nevertheless adopted two more children that month: Tam, a blind Vietnamese girl, and Isaiah Justus, an African-American baby boy.<ref name=OrthNov1992/>\n\nAllen and Previn remained in contact; in July 1992 she lost her job as a summer-camp counselor in Maine after spending too much time on the telephone with a \"Mr. Simon\", who turned out to be Allen.<ref name=Stern10Feb2014/> Allen says that when he visited Connecticut to celebrate Dylan's birthday, Farrow left a note on a door in which she called him a \"child molester\".<ref>\"Allen Said Farrow Made Good On Her Promise\". [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1314&dat=19921123&id=orwzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PPADAAAAIBAJ&pg=1660,2745737&hl=en] ''[[The Spokesman-Review]]'', November 23rd, 1992. (p.1) Retrieved 14 October 2018.</ref> On 1 August 1992, according to the testimony of Dr. Susan Coates, Farrow telephoned Dr. Coates to say she had learned that Previn and Allen were still in a relationship; Farrow was distressed and told Coates that, just a week earlier, she and Allen had talked about getting married; \"Ms. Farrow described Mr. Allen as \"satanic and evil,\" Dr. Coates said, adding that Ms. Farrow pleaded with her to \"find a way to stop him.\"<ref name=Marks30March1993/> Allen publicly announced his relationship with Previn on 17 August 1992. Soon Yi said later that month that Woody Allen had never been a father figure to her, and that they had become friendly only after his romance with Mia Farrow had ended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/soon-yi-speaks-lets-not-get-hysterical-197958|title=Soon-Yi Speaks: 'Let's Not Get Hysterical'|last=EDT|first=Newsweek Staff On 8/30/92 at 8:00 PM|date=1992-08-30|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> As Allen and Mia Farrow had never married, and as Allen had never adopted Soon-Yi, their relationship was not illegal.<ref>[https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/137176042?searchTerm=jack%20waterford%20%22soon-yi%22%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20&searchLimits= \"Modern Reasons For Old Taboos on Incest\".] Jack Waterford, ''[[The Canberra Times]]''. 27 August 1992 (p 9) Retrieved 14th October 2018.</ref> Previn and Allen's relationship did continue, and they were married in Venice on December 23, 1997.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Collins|first1=Glenn|title=Mixed Reviews Greet Woody Allen Marriage| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/12/25/nyregion/mixed-reviews-greet-woody-allen-marriage.html|work=The New York Times|date=December 25, 1997}}</ref>\n\n==Allegation==\nOn August 4, 1992, Allen visited his children at Farrow's country home in Bridgewater, Connecticut, while Farrow and a friend went shopping with the two most recently adopted children, Tam and Isaiah.<ref name=OrthNov1992 /> Farrow and Allen had been due to sign an agreement on August 6, that Allen would pay $6,000 a month for the support of Dylan, Satchel and Moses;<ref name=OrthNov1992/> although Martin Weltz, lawyer of Mia Farrow, said that on August 4 Mia Farrow called him on the phone, to suspend the processing of the agreement.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3uQCAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Everything You Always Wanted to Know About Woody and Mia (But Were Afraid to Ask)|last=Hoban|first=Phoebe|date=September 21, 1992|website=Books Google|publisher=New York Magazine|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nPresent in the house once Farrow had left, were: Dylan; Satchel; Farrow's babysitter, Kristie Groteke; the children's French tutor, Sophie Berge; Farrow's friend's three children; and Farrow's friend's babysitter, Alison Strickland. When Mia Farrow left the house Moses was, according to her, \"off by himself taking a walk\". Moses claimed he was already in the house when Allen arrived.{{sfnp|Farrow|1997|p=270}}<ref name=\"MosesFarrowMay2018\" /> The day after the visit, Stickland told her employer that she had seen Allen kneel on the floor in front of Dylan, then aged seven, with his face in her lap turned toward Dylan's body; she testified to that effect during the custody trial.<ref name=MarksApril101993>{{cite news|last1=Marks|first1=Peter|title=Sitter Questions Allen Actions With Daughter|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/04/10/nyregion/sitter-questions-allen-actions-with-daughter.html|work=The New York Times|date=April 10, 1993}}</ref> (The judge, after hearing the full testimony of Alison Strickland, did not believe that she was describing any kind of abuse or inappropriate behavior) <ref name=\"Shea7Feb2014\" /> Farrow asked Dylan about it, Dylan allegedly described what had happened and said she had not liked it; Farrow telephoned her attorney for guidance and was advised to take Dylan to her local pediatrician. Farrow took Dylan to Dr. Vadakkekara Kavirajan, the regular paediatrician for Farrow's children, where the girl did not make any allegation of abuse.\n\nAccording to the expert hired by Farrow, Farrow had videotaped Dylan's answers to her questions prior to the visit to the pediatrician in which Dylan made the allegation of abuse   \"in fits and starts\", and in a way that \"set a tone for a child about how to answer\",<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mia & Woody : love and betrayal|first=Kristi|last=Groteke|date=1994|publisher=Carroll & Graf|isbn=|pages=169|oclc=1036704501}}</ref> and Dylan told Farrow&nbsp;that she&nbsp;had been with&nbsp;Mr.&nbsp;Allen&nbsp;in&nbsp;the attic,<ref>{{harvnb|Farrow|1997|p=272}}; {{cite news|title=Woody Allen claims videotape proves Mia's 'unfitness' as mother|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1992/12/21/Woody-Allen-claims-videotape-proves-Mias-unfitness-as-mother/4450724914000/|publisher=UPI|date=December 21, 1992}}</ref> and&nbsp;that he had touched&nbsp;her private parts.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thunderpeel2001.com/files/Allen-v-Farrow.pdf|title=Allen v. Farrow (1993)|last=Wilk|first=Elliott, J.|website=|access-date= }}</ref><ref name=Stern10Feb2014/><ref name=OrthNov1992>{{cite news |last=Orth|first=Maureen|author-link=Maureen Orth|title=Mia's Story|magazine=Vanity Fair|date=August 5, 2008|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/archive/1992/11/farrow199211|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221205817/http://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/archive/1992/11/farrow199211|archive-date=November 1992|url-status=live}}</ref> On day six, they returned to the pediatrician where Dylan repeated the allegation; Dr. Kavirajan then informed authorities, although he said he found no physical evidence of sexual molestation.{{sfnp|Farrow|1997|p=272}}<ref name=\"Orth7Feb2014\">{{cite web|last1=Orth|first1=Maureen|title=10 Undeniable Facts About the Woody Allen Sexual-Abuse Allegation|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2014/02/woody-allen-sex-abuse-10-facts|website=Vanity Fair|date=7 February 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"fmw\">[https://www.upi.com/Archives/1992/08/19/Woody-Abuse-charge-video-tape-forced-him-to-seek-childrens-custody/5213714196800/ \"Woody: Abuse charge, video tape forced him to seek children's custody\"] Frederick M Winship. August 19th, 1992. UPI. Retrieved 14 October 2018.</ref> Dr. Kavirajan would later tell an interviewer that he was \"required by state law\" to report any allegations of child abuse.<ref name=\"fmw\" /> Dr. Susan Coates informed Allen of the allegation during one of the sessions in which he was participating in Satchel's therapy; he responded \"I'm completely flabbergasted,\" repeating it several times.<ref name=\"Marks30March1993\" />\n\n==Legal action==\n===Custody proceedings and statements===\nOn August 13, 1992, a week after being told about the allegation, Allen began proceedings in [[New York Supreme Court]] for sole custody of Dylan, Moses, and his and Farrow's biological son, Satchel.<ref name=Weber14Aug1992>{{cite news|last1=Weber|first1=Bruce|title=Woody Allen Files Child-Custody Lawsuit|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/08/14/nyregion/woody-allen-files-child-custody-lawsuit.html|work=The New York Times|date=August 14, 1992}}</ref> Farrow's mother, the actor [[Maureen O'Sullivan]], issued a statement on August 15 that was critical of Allen and said that Farrow had retained [[Alan Dershowitz]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rabinovitz|first1=Jonathan|title=War! Mia Fights Back With (Gasp!) Publicity|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/08/16/nyregion/war-mia-fights-back-with-gasp-publicity.html|work=The New York Times|date=August 16, 1992}}</ref> Two days later, Allen released his first public comment about his relationship with Soon-Yi Previn: \"Regarding my love for Soon-Yi: It's real and happily all true. She's a lovely, intelligent, sensitive woman who has and continues to turn around my life in a wonderfully positive way.\"<ref name=Weber18Aug1992>{{cite news|last1=Weber|first1=Bruce|title=Public Disclosures From the Private Life of Woody Allen|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/08/18/nyregion/public-disclosures-from-the-private-life-of-woody-allen.html|work=The New York Times|date=August 18, 1992}}</ref><ref name=Wilkinson11Jan2018>{{cite news|last1=Wilkinson|first1=Alissa|title=Why Woody Allen hasn't been toppled by the #MeToo reckoning \u2014 yet|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2018/1/11/16635446/woody-allen-dylan-farrow-mia-ronan-sexual-molestation-allegation-metoo|work=Vox|date=January 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn August 18 Allen held a news conference at the [[Plaza Hotel]]. Calling the molestation allegation \"an unconscionable and gruesomely damaging manipulation of innocent children for vindictive and self-serving motives,\" he alleged that, during a meeting on August 13, Farrow's lawyers had demanded $5\u20138 million hush money.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Marks|first1=Peter|title=Dershowitz Says Farrow Involved Him|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/04/16/nyregion/dershowitz-says-farrow-involved-him.html|work=The New York Times|date=August 16, 1992}}</ref><ref name=Barron19Aug1992>{{cite news|last1=Barron|first1=James|title=Striking Back, Woody Allen Denies Child Sex-Abuse Allegation|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/08/19/nyregion/striking-back-woody-allen-denies-child-sex-abuse-allegation.html|work=The New York Times|date=August 19, 1992}}</ref> Dershowitz responded that the lawyers had suggested Allen pay a lump sum in child support, rather than a monthly one, to reduce Allen's interaction with Farrow. It would be $17,000 a month until each child reach the age of 21, $900,000 for College tuition and $2,500,000 for Mia Farrow herself as compensation for her loss of income for the next 10 years. Allen's lawyers declared that Farrow's proposal was that in exchange for the money she would drop the charges of sexual abuse, Dershowitz flatly denied this possibility and noted that he was trying to reach an agreement that would allow the matter not to be made public and convince the Connecticut police that it was best not to intervene and \"decriminalize\" the case, but that the proposal was completely separate and independent of the economic proposal. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1993/04/15/Dershowitz-Woody-is-on-the-road-to-ruin/2543734846400/|title=Dershowitz: Woody is on the road to ruin|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Barron|first1=James|title=Allen 'Spoiled and Mutilated' His Better Self, Farrow Says|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/08/20/nyregion/allen-spoiled-and-mutilated-his-better-self-farrow-says.html|work=The New York Times|date=August 20, 1992}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Goldman|first1=John J.|title=Final Arguments in Allen Custody Trial as Bitter as First|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-05-05/news/mn-31539_1_daughter-farrow|work=Los Angeles Times|date=May 5, 1993}}</ref> On August 20 Allen's publicist announced that Allen had passed a lie detector test.<ref name=Barron21Aug1992/> The following day, Allen gave an interview to [[Walter Isaacson]] of ''Time'' magazine, describing the nude photographs of Previn as a \"lark of a moment\". Of the affair, he said: \"I didn't feel that just because she was Mia's daughter, there was any great moral dilemma. It was a fact, but not one with any great import.\"<ref name=Isaacson31Aug1992/><ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|last1=Hevesi|first1=Dennis|title=Woody Allen Tells His Side to a Magazine|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/08/23/nyregion/woody-allen-tells-his-side-to-a-magazine.html|work=The New York Times|date=August 23, 1992}}</ref>\n\nDuring the fall of 1992, the police interviewed Dylan utilising anatomical dolls. The last of the interviews took place on December 30, 1992, during which Dylan inserted the penis of the male doll into the vagina of the female doll. When the police asked her why she knew that the dolls fit like that, she told them that during the summer her brother Satchel and she had witnessed how Woody Allen introduced his penis into Soon Yi's vagina. \"Daddies do not do this\" she told them, according to the statement, and \"daddies are not supposed to act like boyfriends.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mia & Woody : love and betrayal|first=Kristi|last=Groteke|date=1994|publisher=Carroll & Graf|isbn=|pages=172|oclc=1036704501 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Saw dad, Soon Yi in bed:Woody Kid|last=Hackett|first=Larry|date=1993-01-13|work=New York Daily News|access-date= }}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Dylan Saw It All 7-year-old says she watched Woody, Soon-Yi having sex|last=Kocieniewski|first=David|date=1993-01-13|work=Newsday|access-date=}}</ref>\nThis disclosure was made by Eleanor Alter in the course of the court hearing in which they treated the right of visits in favor of Woody Allen that would govern during the processing of the procedure. The session was suspended due to the seriousness of the allegation.\n\nThe Yale New Haven team had finished interviewing Dylan on November 13, 1992.<ref name=\":2\" /> One of the aspects they had explored was the relationship between boyfriends and girlfriends. In November 1992 that relationship consisted for Dylan in \"kisses and hugs.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Woody Says He's Cleared Report: No sign of sex abuse: Excerpts From the Yale Report|last=Polner|first=Rob|date=1993-03-19|work=Newsday|access-date= }}</ref> The judicial investigation concluded that the sexual relationship between Soon Yi and Allen began in December 1991.<ref name=\"appeal1994\" /> {{cl-span|Allen declared that the allegation that Dylan has witnessed a sexual relationship in summer was not true|date=November 2019|reason= what allegation? THe relationship was stated to start in december 1991 by Allen (prev section)}} because {{cl-span|it was months before his relationship with Soon Yi started|date=November 2019|reason=It? what is it? Also, Allen stated that dec 1991 was the start, so what the \"it\" that was \"months before\" that happened in july/august/september?}},<ref name=\":5\" /> and \"I think that when Mia needs something, she takes our daughter and makes her say it.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Lawyer:kids saw Woody, Soon Yi have sex|last=Associated Press|date=1993-01-13|work=Star-Gazette|page=2}}</ref>\n\nAllen and Farrow reached an agreement through which Allen would not begin visits with Dylan immediately in exchange for Mia Farrow providing a therapist to the child.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Woody & Mia OK shrink for Dylan|last=Hackett|first=Larry|date=1993-01-20|work=Daily News|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Yale\u2013New Haven Hospital team===\nOn August 17, 1992, the [[Connecticut State Police]] announced that they were investigating the molestation allegation.<ref name=Weber18Aug1992/><ref name=Wilkinson11Jan2018/> In September Dylan was referred to the Child Sexual Abuse Clinic of Yale-New Haven Hospital. The referral was made by the Connecticut State Police and the main  questions were: \"Is Dylan telling the truth, and did we think that she was sexually abused?\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://radaronline.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/yale-new-haven-hospital-allen.pdf|title=Child Sexual Abuse Clinic Evaluation of Dylan Farrow|date=1993-03-17|website=Radaronline.|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> Frank Maco, the Connecticut State's Attorney for the Litchfield district, declared in 1997 that he asked the Child Sexual Abuse Clinic of [[Yale\u2013New Haven Hospital]] to evaluate whether Dylan would make a viable witness.<ref name=ThibaultNov1997/><ref name=OrthOct2013/> The professionals of the Clinic met with the police and prosecutor Maco for preliminary information. {{cl-span|They collected more information from one of the detectives, John Mucherino, to be informed about all the data that the police had investigated |date=November 2019|reason-No idea what the hell this means. Suspect the last part of the sentence was left there by mistake after an edit. Something seems missing here}}. Between September 18 and November 13 they conducted a total of nine separate interviews with Dylan and her mother, Mia Farrow. On October 14 they interviewed Dylan's nanny Kristi Groteke, and between November 17 and January 7 they had three interviews with Woody Allen. Finally, they met with Mia Farrow to review the recording she had made of Dylan between August 5 and 6. Sophie Berge, the other nanny present on August 4, was also interviewed as well as the two psychotherapists treating the children, Dr. Coates and Dr. Stcuhtz.<ref name=\"Ewing2006p159\">{{cite book|title=Minds on Trial: Great Cases in Law and Psychology|last1=Ewing|first1=Charles Patrick|last2=McCann|first2=Joseph T.|date=2006|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|at=(pp.&nbsp;153\u2013164), p.&nbsp;159|chapter=Woody Allen and Mia Farrow: A Swing of King Solomon's Sword|ref=harv|author1-link=Charles Patrick Ewing}}</ref><ref name=Winter7Feb2014>{{cite news|last1=Winter|first1=Jessica|title=Woody Allen and Dylan Farrow: Just the Facts|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/life/culturebox/2014/02/woody_allen_and_dylan_farrow_digging_deeper_into_misleading_coverage.html|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Leventhal signed the team's report, while Dylan was interviewed by the social workers.<ref name=Winter7Feb2014/><ref name=OrthOct2013/> Completed in March 1993, the report concluded: \"It is our expert opinion that Dylan was not sexually abused by Mr. Allen.\"{{efn|[[Yale\u2013New Haven Hospital]] Child Sexual Abuse Clinic (1993): \"It is our expert opinion that Dylan was not sexually abused by Mr. Allen. Further, we believe that Dylan\u2019s statements on videotape and her statements to us during our evaluation do not refer to actual events that occurred to her on August 4th, 1992&nbsp;... In developing our opinion we considered three hypotheses to explain Dylan's statements. First, that Dylan\u2019s statements were true and that Mr. Allen had sexually abused her; second, that Dylan\u2019s statements were not true but were made up by an emotionally vulnerable child who was caught up in a disturbed family and who was responding to the stresses in the family; and third, that Dylan was coached or influenced by her mother, Ms. Farrow. While we can conclude that Dylan was not sexually abused, we can not be definite about whether the second formulation by itself or the third formulation by itself is true. We believe that it is more likely that a combination of these two formulations best explains Dylan\u2019s allegations of sexual abuse.\"<ref name=AllenFeb72014/><ref name=Ewing2006p159/><ref name=Winter7Feb2014/>}}\n\nThe team had proposed the study as an attempt to corroborate or falsify some of these basic hypotheses:\n# That the Dylan allegations were true and Allen had sexually abused her.\n# That the statements of Dylan were not true and had been made by an emotionally vulnerable minor trapped in a disturbed family situation and who responded to stress.\n# That she had been taught or influenced by her mother.\n\nThe Team members were the medical director of the Child Sexual Abuse Clinic since its foundation, Dr. John M. Leventhal,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slidex.tips/download/curriculum-vitae-john-m-leventhal-md|title=[PDF] CURRICULUM VITAE. John M. Leventhal, M.D. - Free Download PDF|website=slidex.tips|language=en|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> Dr. Julia Hamilton, who was also social worker and co-director of the Yale Medical Center Child Abuse Program,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/nhregister/obituary.aspx?n=julia-pearl-hamilton&pid=153301737|title=Julia Pearl Hamilton, Obituary.|website=|access-date=}}</ref> and Social Worker Ms. Sawyer, who had a masters in Social Work and ten years of experience. The social workers met Dylan in Yale New Haven every Friday for an hour or so. Kristi Groteke was interviewed for three hours.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=Mia & Woody : love and betrayal|first=Kristi|last=Groteke|date=1994|publisher=Carroll & Graf|isbn=|page=168|oclc=1036704501}}</ref> Maureen Orth stated that its conclusion was based, in part, on the view that Dylan had difficulty telling a consistent story and suffered from \"thought disturbances.\"<ref name=\"Orth7Feb2014\" /> According to the report, the important inconsistencies in Dylan's statement, the lack of spontaneity, and the impression of repeating something learned are the main reason for the conclusions.<ref name=\":2\" /> The report also stressed that Dylan felt that she had to solve her mother's problems,<ref name=\":4\" /> and indicated that the relationship between Mia Farrow and Dylan and Satchel was very disturbed and required immediate intensive psychotherapy.<ref name=\":3\" /> The team destroyed the original notes at the time of incorporating its content into the report.<ref name=\"Orth7Feb2014\" /><ref name=\"Ewing2006p159\" /> The report was immediately sent to the state police who had commissioned it, who informed Mia Farrow that same day and two days before Woody Allen was informed.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mia & Woody : love and betrayal|first=Kristi|last=Groteke|date=1994|publisher=Carroll & Graf|isbn=|pages=222|oclc=1036704501 }}</ref> Maco told a reporter in 1997 that Yale \"took the case and ran away with it.\"<ref name=\"ThibaultNov1997\" />\n\n===Custody trial===\n====Testimony====\nThe custody hearings began on March 19, 1993, in State Supreme Court in Manhattan,<ref name=Perez20March1993>{{cite news|last1=Perez-Pena|first1=Richard|title=Woody Allen Tells of Affair as Custody Battle Begins|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/03/20/nyregion/woody-allen-tells-of-affair-as-custody-battle-begins.html|work=The New York Times|date=March 20, 1993}}</ref> and ended on May 4.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Marks|first1=Peter|title=Allen-Farrow Trial Ends in New Round of Old Charges|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/05/nyregion/allen-farrow-trial-ends-in-new-round-of-old-charges.html|work=The New York Times|date=May 5, 1993}}</ref> Journalists were allowed in court but not with television cameras or microphones.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Penez-Pena|first1=Richard|title=Judge Bars Broadcasters From Farrow-Allen Case|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/12/12/nyregion/judge-bars-broadcasters-from-farrow-allen-case.html|work=The New York Times|date=December 12, 1992}}</ref> Taking the stand on the first day, Allen said the allegation was Farrow's vengeance for his affair with Soon Yi-Previn, which he had not intended to be \"anything but a private thing\"; he had hoped Farrow would not find out about it. He described her anger when she did.<ref name=Perez20March1993/>\n\n[[File:NYC - New York County Supreme Courthouse.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|New York State Supreme Courthouse]]\nKristie Groteke,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Groteke|first1=Kristie|last2=Rosen|first2=Marjorie|title=Mia & Woody: Love and Betrayal|url=https://archive.org/details/miawoodylovebetr00grot|url-access=registration|date=1994|publisher=Carroll & Graf Publishers|location=New York}}</ref> Farrow's babysitter, testified in April that for about 15\u201320 minutes on the afternoon in question, she had not been able to find Dylan or Allen in the house; she had assumed they were outside with the other children.<ref name=Stern10Feb2014/> Allen said he had gone to the bathroom during the disputed period.<ref name=MarksApril101993/> The children's French tutor, Sophie Berge, testified that she had noticed Dylan had been wearing no underwear under her dress that day.<ref name=Stern10Feb2014/><ref name=Winter7Feb2014/><ref name=Wypijewski26Feb2014>{{cite news|last1=Wypijewski|first1=Joann|title=Woody and Mia: A Modern Family Timeline|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/woody-and-mia-modern-family-timeline/|work=The Nation|date=February 26, 2014}}</ref> Another Farrow-household nanny, Monica Thompson, who was not present in the house on that day, told Allen's lawyers in two [[affidavit]]s in February 1993 that she had felt pressured by Farrow to support the allegation.<ref name=latimes020293/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Span|first1=Paula|title=Clash of the Nannies|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1993/04/07/clash-of-the-nannies/97418ba8-5206-4a36-888f-ce1d54b3f84f|work=The Washington Post|date=April 7, 1993}}</ref> Thompson said that Groteke had also had reservations; according to Thompson, Groteke told her, days after the allegation was made, that she \"did not have Dylan out of her sight for longer than five minutes. She did not remember Dylan being without her underwear.\"<ref name=latimes020293>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-02-02/news/mn-952_1_woody-allen|title=Nanny Casts Doubt on Farrow Charges|date=February 2, 1993|first=John J.|last=Goldman|work=Los Angeles Times|archivedate=January 19, 2018| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180119042801/http://articles.latimes.com/1993-02-02/news/mn-952_1_woody-allen|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Wypijewski26Feb2014/> Groteke acknowledged that she had had that conversation, although she only admitted to telling Thompson that she did not remember having lost sight of Dylan.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mia & Woody : love and betrayal|first=Kristi|last=Groteke|date=1994|publisher=Carroll & Graf|isbn=|pages=126|oclc=1036704501}}</ref> Ms. Thompson, who was Dylan's nanny since the girl was two months old, also stated that the charges against Woody Allen brought by Farrow were 'not true'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1993/01/26/Mias-nanny-says-Woody-was-the-better-parent/6587728024400/|title=Mia's nanny says Woody was the better parent|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref> Mavis Smith, the housekeeper of Mia Farrow for thirteen years, said she thought Woody Allen was a good father and in a telephone conversation said that in the thirteen years she had never seen Allen doing something sexual with Dylan or with Satchel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1993/04/06/Expert-witness-doubts-Woody-abused-adopted-daughter/2831734068800/|title=Expert witness doubts Woody abused adopted daughter|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2019-03-23 }}</ref>\n\nDr. Susan Coates, a Farrow family therapist, testified that Farrow had been so angry with Allen when she discovered the affair with Previn that Coates had feared for Allen's safety.<ref name=Marks30March1993>{{cite news|last1=Marks|first1=Peter|title=Doctor Recounts Threats By Farrow Against Allen|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/02/23/reviews/farrow-doctor.html|work=The New York Times|date=March 30, 1993}}</ref>  Farrow's lawyer accused Coates of gullibility for having accepted Allen's version of events.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Grimes|first1=William|title=Farrow's Lawyer Takes Aim at Doctor's Judgment|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/03/31/nyregion/farrow-s-lawyer-takes-aim-at-doctor-s-judgment.html|work=The New York Times|date=March 31, 1993}}</ref> Therapist Dr. Nancy Schultz was hired by Farrow and Allen in April 1991 because the child \"lived in her own fantasy world\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/04/02/nyregion/psychologist-testifies-about-visitation-rights-for-allen.html|title=Psychologist Testifies About Visitation Rights for Allen|last=Marks|first=Peter|date=1993-04-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-31|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Dr. Schultz testified that Dylan has become \"absorbed in what the fantasy is (and) that it became real\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Woody\u00b4s lawyer says Conn. cops siding with Mia|last=Hackett|first=Larry|date=1993-04-09|work=Daily News|access-date=}}</ref>Neither of them, Dr. Coates and Dr. Schultz, believed that sexual abuse had occurred.<ref name=\":0\" /> One of Allen's lawyers alleged that Farrow's lawyers had suggested \"the charges could be made to go away\" if Allen agreed to pay around $7 million. Alan Dershowitz, representing Farrow, said there had been an \"exploratory\" session to attempt mediation. \"To have this described as an extortionate meeting is ridiculous,\" he said. He added that Allen's lawyers were \"trying to set a trap, the trap failed and now they testify as if the trap succeeded\". One of Allen's lawyers acknowledged when cross-examined that the discussion about money related mostly to the children's education and medical care, as well as money owed for Farrow's film work for Allen.<ref name=MarksApril101993/> Levett, Mia Farrow's lawyer, acknowledged that he suggested various amounts to reach an agreement \"For child support, including household help: $17,000 a month until the youngest of the children turned 21, roughly $2.5 million factoring in inflation and interest. For tuition, assuming all three went to college: $800,000 to $900,000. Plus unspecified medical and, yes, psychiatric expenses. There might be a damage claim for Dylan, who had accused her father of molesting her. And some compensation for Mia Farrow, who'd earned $300,000 a year for her roles in Allen's annual films and was entitled to that sum for five to 10 years now that she was out of a job.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1993/04/16/dershowitz-woody-would-not-budge/0a95205b-6ca1-415f-8394-f212f705c954/|title=DERSHOWITZ: WOODY WOULD NOT BUDGE|last=Span|first=Paula|date=April 16, 1993|website=The Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref> \"Mr. Dershowitz echoed Mr. Levett's testimony. But he acknowledged that a proposal was made to intercede in the child-abuse investigation in favor of a private settlement. He added that the offer \"was not premised on any payments.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> In the program of Charlie Rose on October 14, 1992, Dershowitz stated about it: \"I don't think it ever had to come out. If he (Woody Allen) had not filed that suit, I don't think anybody would know the story today and I think it would be resolved quietly behind the scenes.\"<ref>{{Citation|title=Alan Dershowitz - Charlie Rose|url=https://charlierose.com/videos/18189|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\n'''John Leventhal''' of the Yale\u2013New Haven Child Sexual Abuse Clinic testified by [[Deposition (law)|deposition]] on 20 April. Citing inconsistencies in Dylan's account, he said that once it was discarded the hypothesis that Dylan's narrative corresponded to events that actually happened  the  Yale\u2013New Haven team \"had two hypotheses: one, that these were statements that were made by an emotionally disturbed child and then became fixed in her mind. And the other hypothesis was that she was coached or influenced by her mother. We did not come to a firm conclusion. We think that it was probably a combination.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Perez-Pena|first1=Richard|title=Doctor Cites Inconsistencies In Dylan Farrow's Statements|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/04/nyregion/doctor-cites-inconsistencies-in-dylan-farrow-s-statements.html|work=The New York Times|date=May 4, 1993}}</ref> Farrow and Allen both hired experts to discuss the report.<ref name=Ewing2006p159/> '''Anne Meltzer''', a forensic psychologist, testified for Allen that the report had \"reached conclusions that were supported well by the data they collected.\" She said the tape of Dylan making the allegation was \"flawed\" because it had been filmed by one side and not by a professional.<ref name=Ewing2006p159/><ref name=Marks28April1993/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Miller|first1=Tracey L.|title=Judge in Woody-Mia child custody case airs anti-Allen views|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1993/04/26/Judge-in-Woody-Mia-child-custody-case-airs-anti-Allen-views/5124735796800/|publisher=UPI|date=April 26, 1993}}</ref> '''Stephen Herman''', a child psychiatrist, testified for Farrow that the report was \"seriously flawed\", and that he could find no evidence of a thought disorder in Dylan's statements,<ref name=Ewing2006p159/><ref name=Marks28April1993>{{cite news|last1=Marks|first1=Peter|title=Yale Study About Allen Flawed, Expert Testifies|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/04/28/nyregion/yale-study-about-allen-flawed-expert-testifies.html|work=The New York Times|date=April 28, 1993}}</ref> however, Dr. Herman expressly stated that the report was not biased<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1993/04/28/evidence-with-a-double-edge/82fc8e5e-19c5-472a-981e-4adfdfa33b6d/|title=EVIDENCE WITH A DOUBLE EDGE|last=Span|first=Paula|date=1993-04-28|website=The Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Woody vs. Mia case drawing to a close|last=The Associated Press|date=1993-04-28|work=Asbury Park Press (Asbury Park, New Jersey)|access-date=}}</ref> and that he himself, in light of the evidence, could not reach any conclusion regarding the allegation of abuse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1993/04/28/evidence-with-a-double-edge/82fc8e5e-19c5-472a-981e-4adfdfa33b6d/|title=EVIDENCE WITH A DOUBLE EDGE|last=Span|first=Paula|date=1993-04-28|website=The Washington Post.|access-date=}}</ref> That it could have happened, or it could not have happened.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1993/04/27/Woody-Mia-judge-questions-value-of-expert-testimony/6160735883200/|title=Woody-Mia judge questions value of expert testimony|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2019-03-21 }}</ref> That the evidence was inconclusive.<ref name=\"Shea7Feb2014\" /> To [[Charles Patrick Ewing]] and Joseph McCann, the most damaging criticism of the report was that the team had destroyed its notes from the interviews it conducted, which meant the court could not test the validity of the report's conclusions; they write that forensic experts have an obligation to retain their notes for review. Another criticism was that the team was unwilling to testify in court, except via Leventhal's deposition.{{sfnp|Ewing|McCann|2006|p=160}} Dr. Herman also recognized the tape of Dylan making the allegation was flawed because it was made in a way that \"set a tone for a child about how to answer\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mia & Woody : love and betrayal|first=Kristi|last=Groteke|date=1994|publisher=Carroll & Graf|isbn=|pages=169|oclc=1036704501 }}</ref> He also concluded that there was no point in passing another forensic evaluation to Dylan on the allegation.<ref name=\"Shea7Feb2014\" />\n\nAll the psychiatric experts who declared in the trial agreed that Allen was able to fulfill a positive role in Dylan's therapy.<ref name=\"appeal1994\" /><ref name=\"Shea7Feb2014\" />\n\n====Decision====\nIn his 33-page decision in June 1993,<ref name=Shea7Feb2014/> Justice Elliott Wilk rejected Allen's bid for custody of the three children and rejected the allegation of sexual abuse, denied Allen immediate visitation rights with Dylan, saying of Allen's behavior toward Dylan that it was \"grossly inappropriate and that measures must be taken to protect her\" while pointing out that Allen's inappropriate behavior was not sexual in nature.<ref name=Shea7Feb2014/><ref name=Marks8June1993/>{{sfnp|Ewing|McCann|2006|p=161}} His criticism of Allen's parenting was harsh.{{sfnp|Ewing|McCann|2006|pp=160\u2013161}}<ref name=Stern10Feb2014/> Rejecting Allen's portrayal of Farrow as a \"woman scorned\", Wilk said there was no credible evidence that she had coached Dylan  although the videotape she made of Dylan compromised the investigation of sexual abuse, and he criticized Allen for his \"trial strategy\" of turning family members and employees against one another. The Yale\u2013New Haven team's unwillingness to testify in court, except through Leventhal's deposition, together with the destruction of its notes, had rendered its report, he wrote, \"sanitized and, therefore, less credible\".{{sfnp|Ewing|McCann|2006|p=160}}<ref name=Stern10Feb2014/><ref name=Shea7Feb2014>{{cite news|last1=Shea|first1=Danny|title=Here's The 1993 Woody Allen Custody Ruling In Its Damning, Detailed Entirety|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/danny-shea/heres-the-1993-woody-alle_b_4746866.html|work=HuffPost|date=February 7, 2014}}; {{cite court | litigants = Allen v. Farrow (1993) | court = N.Y. Sup. | date = June 7, 1993 }}</ref><ref name=Marks8June1993>{{cite news|last1=Marks|first1=Peter|title=Allen Loses to Farrow in Bitter Custody Battle|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/02/23/reviews/farrow-verdict.html|work=The New York Times|date=June 8, 1993}}</ref> Wilk called the case \"frivolous\" and ordered Allen to pay Farrow's costs,<ref name=Marks8June1993/>{{sfnp|Ewing|McCann|2006|p=161}} Regarding the allegation of abuse, Wilk concluded that the evidence did not support that it had occurred, although he was not sure that the evidence demonstrated conclusively that it had not happened. The judge did not order a new battery of forensic evidence with Dylan because all the experts agreed with the conclusions expressed by the expert appointed by Farrow and that it would not be beneficial, nor would it provide useful information. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Criminal inquiry, social services===\nThe police interviewed Allen in Litchfield in January 1993 for over three hours. He said he had never been in the attic crawl space; when the police said they had taken fingerprints in there, he said it was possible that his prints were there. The forensic specialist chief of Connecticut\u2019s state crime laboratory,  Dr.Henry Lee, said that what police has found in the crawl space was hair fibers   and that the evidence could not place Allen in the attic.  On September 20 that year, Frank Maco, the State's Attorney, accompanied by a female police detective, talked to Dylan; Maco told a reporter in 1997: \"I saw complete withdrawal any time I tried to discuss the incident.\"<ref name=ThibaultNov1997/><ref name=OrthOct2013/>\n\nOn September 24, 1993, Maco held a news conference to say that he would not pursue the molestation allegation, despite having [[probable cause]], citing a desire not to traumatize Dylan.<ref name=ThibaultNov1997>{{cite news|last1=Thibault|first1=Andy|title=People: Frank Maco|url=http://www.connecticutmag.com/the-connecticut-story/mia-farrow-s-vanity-fair-interview-references-connecticut-magazine-article/article_4327cac7-ffef-5eb5-9c19-fdaf70e84855.html|work=Connecticut Magazine|date=November 1997}}</ref><ref name=Henneberger25Sept1993>{{cite news |first=Melinda|last=Henneberger|url = https://www.nytimes.com/1993/09/25/nyregion/connecticut-prosecutor-won-t-file-charges-against-woody-allen.html | title = Connecticut Prosecutor Won't File Charges Against Woody Allen | work = The New York Times | date = September 25, 1993}}</ref><ref name=CBS18Jan2018>{{cite news|title=Dylan Farrow details her sexual molestation allegations against Woody Allen|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/dylan-farrow-interview-today-gayle-king-full-transcript-woody-allen-me-too/|publisher=CBS News|date=January 18, 2018}}</ref> In the official Statement of decision of the prosecution, Frank Maco acknowledged that even in the case of custody and with a more favorable standard of proof for the accusation that \"proof beyond a reasonable doubt\" it had been impossible to reach the conclusion that the abuse had occurred. He also acknowledged that the nature of the evidence was a fertile ground for the defense and \u201cwould not have the same probative  as it did in the New York Supreme Court custody case\u201d; so he considered  his duty \u201cto avoid the unjustifiable risk of exposing a child to the rigors and uncertainties of a questionable prosecution\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/204662575/Statement-of-Decision-9-24-1993|title=Statement of Decision 9-24-1993|website=Scribd|language=en|access-date=2019-05-04}}</ref>\n\nIn a letter to the New York Department of Social Services, Allen's psychotherapist Kathryn Prescott stated that Allen's psychological profile \"was definitely not that of a sexual offender\" and also stated \u201cThere has never been any suggestion that Mr. Allen was suffering from a sexual perversion / deviant sexual behavior.\"<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1241&dat=19930421&id=Y35TAAAAIBAJ&sjid=FIYDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6340,6035301&hl=en \"Therapist says Woody Allen No Sex Offender\"]. Jeanne King, ''[[Daily News (Kingsport)|Daily News]]'', (p.12) April 21st, 1993. Retrieved 14 October 2018.</ref> The New York Department of Social Services closed its own 14-month investigation in October 1993; its letter to Allen stated: \"No credible evidence was found that the child named in this report has been abused or maltreated. This report has, therefore, been considered unfounded.\"<ref name=\"PerezPena26Oct1993\">{{cite news|last1=P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a|first1=Richard|title=Agency Drops Abuse Inquiry in Allen Case|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/26/nyregion/agency-drops-abuse-inquiry-in-allen-case.html|work=The New York Times|date=October 26, 1993}}</ref>\n\nAllen filed complaints with the Connecticut Criminal Justice Commission and the statewide bar counsel over Maco's statement about probable cause.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Perez-Pena|first1=Richard|title=Woody Allen Asks Connecticut to Discipline Prosecutor|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/14/nyregion/woody-allen-asks-connecticut-to-discipline-prosecutor.html|work=The New York Times|date=October 14, 1993}}</ref> The former dismissed the complaint in November 1993.<ref name=Kennedy4Nov1993>{{cite news|last1=Kennedy|first1=Randy|title=Woody Allen Fails to Beat A Prosecutor|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/11/04/nyregion/woody-allen-fails-to-beat-a-prosecutor.html|work=The New York Times|date=November 4, 1993}}</ref> In February 1994 the statewide Grievance Committee ruled that, while Maco had not violated the state's code of conduct for lawyers, his statement was a cause of \"grave concern.\" In addition, Maco had sent a copy of his statement to the judge who was deciding whether to overturn Allen's adoption of Dylan and Moses. That act was \"inappropriate, unsolicited and potentially prejudicial,\" the panel ruled.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Perez-Pena|first1=Richard|title=Panel Criticizes Prosecutor In Inquiry on Woody Allen|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/02/24/nyregion/panel-criticizes-prosecutor-in-inquiry-on-woody-allen.html|work=The New York Times|date=February 24, 1994}}</ref>\n\n===Allen's appeals, other legal action===\nIn December 1992 Farrow began legal action, which was ultimately unsuccessful, to have Allen's adoption of Dylan and Moses declared void. Her position was based, in part, on her view that Allen's affair with Soon-Yi Previn had begun before the adoption was finalized on December 17, 1991.<ref name=Perez19June1993>{{cite news|last1=Perez-Pena|first1=Richard|title=Farrow Spurns Allen's Plea For a Truce|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/06/10/nyregion/farrow-spurns-allen-s-plea-for-a-truce.html|work=The New York Times|date=June 19, 1993}}</ref><ref name=Stern10Feb2014/> Allen stated that the sexual relationship had started in the last week of 1991.<ref name=Perez19June1993/> Allen offered not to appeal the custody ruling if Farrow would drop her attempt to have his adoption of Dylan and Moses declared void, but she refused.<ref name=Perez19June1993/>\n\nIn January 1994 Allen appealed Wilk's decision.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Perez Pena|first1=Richard|title=Woody Allen Appeals Judgment in Custody Case|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/01/14/nyregion/woody-allen-appeals-judgment-in-custody-case.html|work=The New York Times|date=January 14, 1994}}</ref> Of the molestation allegation, the appellate court  concluded \"the evidence in support of the allegations remains inconclusive,\" stated that its \"review of the record militates against a finding that Ms. Farrow fabricated the allegations without any basis\" and explicitly corrected Justice Wilk by stating that the Yale\u2013New Haven team's view that Dylan had a tendency to \"withdraw into a fantasy,\" and that she had offered inconsistent accounts, had to be taken into account. As elements suggesting that the abuse could have occurred but not being sufficient for this conclusion to be more likely than the contrary the court list \"the testimony given at trial by the individuals caring for the children that day, the videotape of Dylan made by Ms. Farrow the following day and the accounts of Dylan's behavior toward Mr. Allen both before and after the alleged instance of abuse.\" The court was critical of Allen's parenting skills and relationship with Soon-Yi Previn. The appeal failed, although two of the five judges said the visitation rights regarding Satchel were too restrictive.<ref name=appeal1994>[https://www.leagle.com/decision/1994524197ad2d3271461 Allen v. Farrow (1994)] (Appellate Division of the Supreme Court of the State of New York, First Department, May 12, 1994).</ref> Allen appealed again, and in July 1995 the [[New York Court of Appeals]] upheld the original decision.<ref name=appeal1995>[https://www.leagle.com/decision/1995352215ad2d1371310 Allen v. Farrow (1995)] (Appellate Division of the Supreme Court of the State of New York, First Department, May 4, 1995).{{pb}}\n{{cite news|last1=Brozan|first1=Nadine|title=Chronicle|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/07/06/style/chronicle-460695.html|work=The New York Times|date=July 6, 1995}}</ref>\n\n==Later statements, reception==\n===''What Falls Away''===\nIn Mia Farrow's 1997 memoir, ''What Falls Away'', Farrow repeated the accusation that Allen had sexually abused Dylan Farrow.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Farrow|first1=Mia|title=What Falls Away|date=1997|publisher=Bantam|location=New York|page=271|ref=harv}}</ref> Farrow's abuse allegation was mentioned in several of the book's reviews.<ref>\" Ms. Farrow claimed that Mr. Allen had long been focusing inappropriate sexual attention on their 7-year-old adoptive daughter Dylan.\"[https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/books/98/02/01/bsp/25818.html]\"Intimate Strangers\". [[Kathryn Harrison]], ''[[The New York Times]]'' 23rd February, 1997. Retrieved 14th October, 2018.</ref><ref>\"In Farrow's life, apparently, no gruesome situation goes untopped: She further claims that Allen was guilty of sexually abusing her 7-year-old adopted daughter.\" [http://articles.latimes.com/1997-03-02/books/bk-33844_1_mia-farrow \"Rosemary's Mother\".] Celia McGee, ''[[LA Times]], March 2nd, 1997. Retrieved October 14th, 2018.</ref>\n\n===Siblings, open letter===\n[[File:Ronan Farrow, Ukraine, 23 March 2012 (cropped) .jpg|thumb|left|[[Ronan Farrow]], 2012]]\nWhen Allen won the [[Golden Globe Cecil B. DeMille Award]] in January 2014, Mia Farrow and Satchel (now going under the name [[Ronan Farrow]] and working as a journalist) tweeted objections.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pulver|first1=Andrew|title=Woody Allen Golden Globe greeted with derision by Mia and Ronan Farrow|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jan/13/golden-globes-woody-allen-mia-farrow-tweet|work=The Guardian|date=January 13, 2014}}</ref> Dylan Farrow, by then 28, repeated the molestation allegation the following month in an open letter in ''The New York Times'' blog of [[Nicholas Kristof]], a family friend. Writing that Allen had made her feel uncomfortable \"for as long as [she] could remember\", she alleged, for example, that he would get into bed with her in his underwear and that she would hide to avoid him.<ref name=Farrow1Feb2014>{{cite news|first=Dylan|last=Farrow|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/02/opinion/sunday/kristof-dylan-farrows-story.html |title=Dylan Farrow's Story |work=The New York Times |date=February 1, 2014}}</ref> Allen called the allegations \"untrue and disgraceful\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Woody Allen Calls Sexual Abuse Claims 'Untrue and Disgraceful'|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/woody-allen-calls-sexual-abuse-claims-untrue-and-disgraceful-1201083173/|work=Variety|date=February 2, 2014}}</ref> and responded with an op-ed in ''The New York Times''.<ref name=AllenFeb72014>{{cite news|last1=Allen|first1=Woody|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/09/opinion/sunday/woody-allen-speaks-out.html|title=Woody Allen Speaks Out|work=The New York Times|date=February 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Thibault|first1=Andy|title=Cool Justice: New York Times bent rules for Woody Allen, but not for Frank Maco|url=http://www.nhregister.com/columns/article/Cool-Justice-New-York-Times-bent-rules-for-Woody-11384930.php|work=New Haven Register|date=February 14, 2014}}</ref> The newspaper allowed Dylan's open letter 936 words within Kristof's blog, Ronan wrote, while Allen's op-ed was given twice the length and published in the print edition.<ref name=Farrow11May2016/>\n\nRonan, aged four in 1992, has been critical of Allen for several years; in 2011 he tweeted: \"He's my father married to my sister. That makes me his son and his brother-in-law. That is such a moral transgression.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ullman|first1=Joan|title=Ronan Farrow: Man on a Mission|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/uncharted-customs/201801/ronan-farrow-man-mission|work=Psychology Today|date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> In ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' in May 2016, he wrote that, following the publication of Dylan's open letter, his colleagues had forwarded him the daily emails \"blasted out by Allen's powerful publicist\", with an open [[Carbon copy|cc list]], offering talking points for reporters and the names of friends, therapists and lawyers willing to be interviewed. He wrote: \"Reporters on the receiving end of this kind of PR blitz have to wonder if deviating from the talking points might jeopardize their access to all the other A-list clients.\"<ref name=Farrow11May2016>{{Cite news|first=Ronan|last=Farrow|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/my-father-woody-allen-danger-892572|title=My Father, Woody Allen, and the Danger of Questions Unasked (Guest Column)|newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date= May 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDylan's brother Moses Farrow, who was 14 in 1992, has taken a different view; he has reconciled with Allen and is now estranged from the Farrow family. When Dylan published her open letter, he said in an interview that several people had been in the house on the disputed day and that \"no one, not my father or sister, was off in any private spaces\". He asserted that Mia Farrow had cultivated a climate in which he and his siblings had felt compelled to support her views, and that she had both physically and emotionally abused him.<ref>{{cite news|first=Michael|last=Rothman|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/dylan-farrows-brother-moses-mia-farrow-woody-allen/story?id=22377303|title=Dylan Farrow's Brother Moses Says Mia Farrow, Not Woody Allen Was Abusive |publisher= ABC News |date= February 5, 2014}}{{pb}}\n{{cite news|first=Andrew|last=Pulver|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/feb/05/woody-allen-dylan-farrow-moses|title=Moses Farrow defends Woody Allen over child abuse allegations |date=5 February 2013|work= The Guardian}}</ref> He repeated the allegations in 2017 to [[Eric Lax]], one of Allen's biographers.<ref>{{cite book|first=Eric|last=Lax|author-link=Eric Lax|url=|title=Start To Finish: Woody Allen and the Art of MovieMaking |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf |location=New York|date=2017|pp=123\u2013129}}</ref> Moses Farrow offered additional details defending Allen in a May 23, 2018 blog post.<ref name=MosesFarrowMay2018>{{cite web|url=https://mosesfarrow.blogspot.nl/2018/05/a-son-speaks-out-by-moses-farrow.html|title=A Son Speaks Out |first=Moses |last=Farrow |publisher=Moses Farrow official blog|date=May 23, 2018|accessdate=May 26, 2018|archivedate=May 26, 2018|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180526025527/http://mosesfarrow.blogspot.com/2018/05/a-son-speaks-out-by-moses-farrow.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In that letter he accused [[Mia Farrow]] of child abuse and neglect, coupled with a [[white savior]] complex: \"When Soon-Yi was young, Mia once threw a large porcelain centerpiece at her head. Luckily it missed, but the shattered pieces hit her legs. Years later, Mia beat her with a telephone receiver.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/moses-farrow-defends-woody-allen-claims-mia-farrow-was-abusive-1114452|title=Woody Allen's Son Moses Farrow Defends Father, Claims Mother Mia Farrow Was Abusive|work= The Hollywood Reporter | first=Evan|last= Real|date=May 23, 2018|accessdate=June 9, 2018|archivedate=June 1, 2018| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180601193441/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/moses-farrow-defends-woody-allen-claims-mia-farrow-was-abusive-1114452|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=MosesFarrowMay2018 /> However, the most important part of Moses' testimony is related to Dylan's allegation of sexual abuse. Moses explains that on the afternoon of August 4 he was at home: \"As the \u201cman of the house\u201d that day, I had promised to keep an eye out for any trouble, and I was doing just that. I remember where Woody sat in the TV room, and I can picture where Dylan and Satchel were. Not that everybody stayed glued to the same spot, but I deliberately made sure to note everyone's coming and going. I do remember that Woody would leave the room on occasion, but never with Dylan. He would wander into another room to make a phone call, read the paper, use the bathroom, or step outside to get some air and walk around the large pond on the property.\"<ref name=\"MosesFarrowMay2018\" /> Moses also indicates that the memory that his sister keeps from having suffered abuse while focusing her attention on an electric train set is not possible: \"It\u2019s a precise and compelling narrative, but there\u2019s a major problem: there ''was'' no electric train set in that attic. There was, in fact, no way for kids to play up there, even if we had wanted to. It was an unfinished crawl space, under a steeply-angled gabled roof, with exposed nails and floorboards, billows of fiberglass insulation, filled with mousetraps and droppings and stinking of mothballs, and crammed with trunks full of hand-me-down clothes and my mother\u2019s old wardrobes. The idea that the space could possibly have accommodated a functioning electric train set, circling around the attic, is ridiculous.\"<ref name=\"MosesFarrowMay2018\" />\n\n===Op-ed and interview===\n{{see also|Weinstein effect|Me Too (hashtag)|Time's Up (movement)}}\n{{external media\n| float  = right\n| width  = 240px\n| image1 = [https://cbsnews3.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2018/01/16/b309fed0-671f-43e1-9d6a-1e8da4bb86a0/thumbnail/1200x630/1ccd4065fabab5f850a3528aedf7d545/ctm-dylan-farrow-gayle-king.jpg Dylan Farrow] ''(left)'' speaks to [[Gayle King]], ''CBS This Morning'', January 18, 2018.\n}}\nIn December 2017, following the Weinstein controversy, Dylan Farrow wrote an op-ed in the ''Los Angeles Times'' asking, \"Why has the #MeToo revolution spared Woody Allen?\"<ref name=Farrow7Dec2017>{{cite news|first=Dylan|last=Farrow |url=http://www.latimes.com/opinion/op-ed/la-oe-farrow-woody-allen-me-too-20171207-story.html |title=Dylan Farrow: Why has the #MeToo revolution spared Woody Allen? |work=The Los Angeles Times|date=December 7, 2017}}</ref> She repeated the molestation allegation in January 2018 in a television interview with [[Gayle King]] for ''[[CBS This Morning]]''.<ref name=CBS18Jan2018/> Allen issued a statement in response:\n\n{{quote|[E]ven though the Farrow family is cynically using the opportunity afforded by the Time's Up movement to repeat this discredited allegation, that doesn't make it any more true today than it was in the past. I never molested my daughter \u2013 as all investigations concluded a quarter of a century ago.<ref name=CBS2018re />}}\n\n[[File:Woody Allen statue, Oviedo, Spain, November 2014.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|left|Statue in [[Oviedo]]]]\nAfter Dylan Farrow's 2014 open letter, several actors issued statements critical of Allen, including [[Rosie O'Donnell]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Rosie O'Donnell says she believes Dylan Farrow's allegations|url=https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/TV/2014/02/07/Rosie-ODonnell-says-she-believes-Dylan-Farrows-allegations/UPI-73171391796252/|publisher=UPI|date=February 2, 2014}}</ref> [[Lena Dunham]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nianias|first1=Helen|title=Lena Dunham rips into Woody Allen and calls him a 'perv' at Sundance|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/lena-dunham-rips-into-woody-allen-and-calls-him-a-perv-at-sundance-10002087.html|work=The Independent|date=January 26, 2015}}</ref> [[Sarah Silverman]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Miller|first1=Julie|title=Is It Wrong to Work with Woody Allen?|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/07/woody-allen-kate-winslet-justin-timberlake-movie|work=Vanity Fair|date=July 7, 2016}}</ref> and [[Susan Sarandon]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lang|first1=Brent|title=Susan Sarandon on Woody Allen: 'He Sexually Assaulted a Child'|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/markets-festivals/susan-sarandon-woody-allen-rape-1201775122/|work=Variety|date=May 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe mood changed further as a result of the #MeToo and Time's Up movements and Dylan's op-ed. In November 2017 during a [[International Day for the Elimination of Violence against Women|women's rally]], a banner referring to the allegation was hung around the neck of Allen's statue in [[Oviedo]], Spain, and a women's group later asked that the statue be removed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2018/01/22/an-abuser-and-pervert-women-in-spain-want-a-statue-of-woody-allen-removed/|title='An abuser and pervert': Women in Spain want a statue of Woody Allen removed|work=The Washington Post|first=Amanda|last=Erickson|date=January 22, 2018}}{{pb}}{{cite news|url=https://www.thelocal.es/20180122/women-demand-woody-allen-statue-removed-in-oviedo-after-sex-molestation-allegations|title=Women demand Woody Allen statue removed in Oviedo after sex molestation allegations|work=The Local Spain|first=Fiona|last=Govan|date=January 22, 2018}}{{pb}}\n{{cite news|title=A man looks at a banner on sculpture of Woody Allen during the rally on the World Day for the Elimination of Violence against Women in Oviedo|url=http://news.trust.org/item/20171125172209-q3evk|agency=Reuters|date=November 25, 2017}}</ref> From October 2017 statements supportive of Dylan, or expressing regret at having worked with Allen, were issued by [[Griffin Newman]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2017/10/tick-actor-griffin-newman-regrets-working-with-woody-allen.html|title=The Tick Actor Griffin Newman Regrets Working With Woody Allen, Promises to Donate His Salary From the Film|website=Vulture.com|first=Jackson|last=McHenry|date=October 16, 2017}}</ref> [[Ellen Page]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/11/ellen-page-brett-ratner-facebook-post|work=Vanity Fair|title= Ellen Page Accuses Brett Ratner of 'Homophobic and Abusive Behavior'|first=Yohan|last=Desata|date=November 10, 2017| accessdate=June 9, 2018| archivedate=January 29, 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.is/KwFLK|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=EllenPageFacebook>{{cite web| url=https://www.facebook.com/EllenPage/posts/10155212835577449| first=Ellen|last=Page|authorlink=Ellen Page|title='You should fuck her to make her realize she's gay'|publisher= Ellen Page verified [[Facebook]]|date=November 10, 2017| accessdate=June 9, 2018| archivedate= January 29, 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.is/WdRhV|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Evan Rachel Wood]],<ref>{{cite tweet|user= evanrachelwood|number=805397149282422784|title=That was years before I read Dylan's letter|first=Evan |last=Rachel Wood|date=December 4, 2016|authorlink=Evan Rachel Wood|accessdate=January 18, 2018|archivedate=June 9, 2018| archiveurl=https://archive.is/tJcEH|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brit.co/evan-rachel-wood-just-took-a-stance-against-this-hollywood-heavyweight-following-maria-schneiders-sexual-assault-revelation/|title= Evan Rachel Wood Just Took a Stand Against This Hollywood Heavyweight|publisher=[[Brit + Co]]|first=Nicole |last= Briese|date =December 5, 2016 |accessdate=June 9, 2018|archivedate=June 9, 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.is/GGlE0|url-status=live}}</ref> [[David Krumholtz]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Verhoeven |first=Beatrice |title='Wonder Wheel' Actor Calls Working With Woody Allen 'One of My Most Heartbreaking Mistakes'|work=TheWrap |date=January 6, 2018|url-status=live |url=https://www.thewrap.com/wonder-wheel-david-krumholtz-regrets-working-with-woody-allen/}}</ref> [[Greta Gerwig]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bruni|first1=Frank|last2=Gerwig|first2=Greta|last3=Sorkin|first3=Aaron|title=Greta Gerwig, Aaron Sorkin: Hollywood Must Change|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/09/opinion/greta-gerwig-woody-allen-aaron-sorkin.html|work=The New York Times|date=January 9, 2018}}</ref> [[Mira Sorvino]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Sorvino |first=Mira |url= https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/mira-sorvino-letter-dylan-farrow_us_5a56b660e4b08a1f624b47e0|title=Exclusive: Mira Sorvino's Open Letter To Dylan Farrow |work=HuffPost |date=January 11, 2018}}</ref> [[Rebecca Hall]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Levin|first1=Sam|title=Rebecca Hall says she won't work with Woody Allen again|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jan/12/rebecca-hall-woody-allen-dylan-farrow|work=The Guardian|date=12 January 2018}}</ref> [[Timoth\u00e9e Chalamet]],<ref name=Harmon16Jan2018>{{cite news|last1=Harmon|first1=Steph|title=Timoth\u00e9e Chalamet: 'I don't want to profit from my work on Woody Allen's film'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jan/16/timothee-chalamet-i-dont-want-to-profit-from-my-work-on-woody-allens-film|work=The Guardian|date=16 January 2018}}</ref> [[Rachel Brosnahan]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/rachel-brosnahan-says-she-regrets-working-woody-allen-1075123|title=Rachel Brosnahan Says She Regrets Working With Woody Allen|work=The Hollywood Reporter|first=Scott|last=Feinberg|date=January 17, 2018}}</ref> [[Natalie Portman]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/5106106/woody-allen-dylan-farrow-actors/|title=These Actors All Worked With Woody Allen. Now They Regret It and Support Dylan Farrow|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|first=Samantha|last=Cooney|date=January 18, 2018}}</ref> [[Colin Firth]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jan/18/colin-firth-woody-allen-accusations-film|title=Colin Firth says he will not work with Woody Allen again|website=The Guardian|first=Sam|last=Levin|date=January 18, 2018}}{{pb}}\n{{cite news|last1=Leszkiewicz|first1=Anna|title=Sadly, Colin Firth's words on Woody Allen have a power that women's don't|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/culture/film/2018/01/sadly-colin-firth-s-words-woody-allen-have-power-women-s-don-t|work=New Statesman|date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> [[Hayley Atwell]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jan/28/hayley-atwell-interview-dry-powder|title=Hayley Atwell: 'It's very liberating to play someone who's unapologetically ruthless'|website=The Guardian|first=Michael|last=Hogan|date=January 28, 2018}}</ref> [[Freida Pinto]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/jan/27/freida-pinto-i-wouldnt-work-with-woody-allen-again|title=Freida Pinto: 'I wouldn't work with Woody Allen again'|website=[[The Guardian]]|first=Simon|last=Hattenstone|date=January 27, 2019|accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref> and [[John Turturro]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/john-turturro-interview-gloria-bell-woody-allen-going-place-the-big-lebowski-a8946846.html|title=John Turturro interview: 'I wouldn't cast Woody Allen now'|website=[[The Independent]]|date=June 7, 2019|accessdate=June 8, 2019}}</ref> Newman, Hall, Chalamet and Fanning said they would donate their earnings from Allen's film ''[[A Rainy Day in New York]]'' (2018) to charities.<ref name=\"Harmon16Jan2018\" />\n\nIn January 2018, the [[Goodspeed Opera House]] in Connecticut canceled its adaptation of Allen's film ''[[Bullets over Broadway]]'' (1994).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/25/theater/woody-allen-bullets-over-broadway.html|title=Goodspeed Cancels Woody Allen Musical|last1=Paulson|first1=Michael|date=June 25, 2018|work=The New York Times}}</ref> In February 2018, Circle Theater in [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]] also canceled their adaptation of ''Bullets over Broadway''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/grand-rapids/index.ssf/2018/02/grand_rapids_theater_latest_to.html|title=Grand Rapids theater cancels Woody Allen's musical in support of #MeToo|last=Martinez|first=Shandra|date=February 1, 2018|publisher=MLive.com|accessdate= February 1, 2018|archivedate=June 9, 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.is/Ihhp4| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Elle Fanning]] stated that she regretted her decision \"if it hurt anyone\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2018/03/11/elle-fanning-regrets-working-woody-allen-upset-7378123/|title=Elle Fanning only regrets working with Woody Allen if you've been upset by it|date=2018-03-11|website=Metro|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref> Joaquin Phoenix stated, \"When I worked with Woody, I knew about the stuff that had come up years ago, I know his daughter ended up writing an open letter. I was not aware of that when we worked together.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2018/01/22/joaquin-phoenix-working-woody-allen-knew-stuff-had-come-up-years-ago/1052501001/|title=Joaquin Phoenix 'not aware' of Dylan Farrow's open letter when he worked with Woody Allen|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref> When asked if he'd work with Allen, [[Peter Sarsgaard]] said \"it's such a complicated question. I've already done a Woody Allen movie\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/movies/peter-sarsgaard-wont-work-woody-allen-again-jeff-daniels-remains-undecided/|title=Peter Sarsgaard Says He Won't Work with Woody Allen Again, But Jeff Daniels Remains Undecided|website=PEOPLE.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref> [[Chloe Sevigny]] stated \u201cI have my own turmoil that I\u2019m grappling with over that decision, would I work with him again? Probably not.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/chloe-sevigny-woody-allen-melinda-and-melinda-1202670722/|title=Chloe Sevigny Says She Would 'Probably Not' Work With Woody Allen Again (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Setoodeh|first=Ramin|last2=Setoodeh|first2=Ramin|date=2018-01-20|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref> [[Marion Cotillard]] when asked replied, \"I have to say today, yeah, if he were to ask me again \u2026 I don\u2019t think it would ever happen because the experience we had together was very odd. I admire some of his work but we had no connection on set.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jan/19/marion-cotillard-woody-allen-experience-midnight-in-paris|title=Marion Cotillard on Woody Allen: 'The experience we had together was very odd'|last=staff|first=Guardian|date=2018-01-19|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-07-24|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nThose expressing support for Allen included [[Barbara Walters]] and [[Diane Keaton]] in 2014,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rayman|first1=Noah|title=Barbara Walters Defends Woody Allen|url=http://time.com/3883/barbara-walters-defends-woody-allen-amid-abuse-claims/|work=Variety|date=February 4, 2014}}{{pb}}{{cite news|last1=Brockes|first1=Emma|title=Diane Keaton: 'I love Woody. And I believe my friend'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/may/03/diane-keaton-i-love-woody-allen-i-believe-my-friend|work=The Guardian|date=May 3, 2014}}</ref> as well as [[Javier Bardem]], [[Jude Law]], [[Alec Baldwin]], [[Bill Maher]], and Keaton again in January 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/04/javier-bardem-woody-allen|title=Javier Bardem Is on Woody Allen's Side: \"I Am Very Shocked by This Sudden Treatment\"|last=Nast|first=Cond\u00e9|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/nov/20/jude-law-shelving-woody-allen-amazon-studios-shame-rainy-day-new-york|title='A terrible shame': Jude Law defends Woody Allen film after Amazon shelves it|last=Pulver|first=Andrew|date=2018-11-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-07-24|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Chuba|first1=Kirsten|title=Alec Baldwin Criticizes Stars Denouncing Woody Allen: 'It's Unfair and Sad'|url=https://variety.com/2018/biz/news/alec-baldwin-stars-denouncing-woody-allen-unfair-and-sad-1202665291/|work=Variety|date=January 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/diane-keaton-defends-woody-allen-sexual-abuse-1202680654/|title=Diane Keaton Defends Woody Allen: 'I Continue to Believe Him'|last=Fernandez|first=Matt|date=2018-01-29|work=Variety|access-date=2018-05-03|language=en-US}}</ref> [[Robert B. Weide]], who made a documentary film on Allen,<ref>{{Citation|last=Weide|first=Robert B.|title=Woody Allen: A Documentary|date=2011-11-20|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1895299/|others=Woody Allen, Letty Aronson, Marshall Brickman|accessdate=2018-03-08}}</ref> published his rebuttals to the Farrow allegations in an article ''The Woody Allen Allegations: Not So Fast''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/01/27/the-woody-allen-allegations-not-so-fast|title=The Woody Allen Allegations: Not So Fast|last=Weide|first=Robert B.|date=2014-01-27|work=The Daily Beast|access-date=2018-03-08|language=en}}</ref> [[Cherry Jones]], addressing the topic, said, \"There are those who are comfortable in their certainty. I am not. I don't know the truth ... When we condemn by instinct our democracy is on a slippery slope.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ryzik|first1=Melena|last2=Barnes|first2=Brooks|title=Can Woody Allen Work in Hollywood Again?|url= https://nyti.ms/2Fovqcm |work=The New York Times|date=January 28, 2018}}</ref> [[Emily Mortimer]], when asked about Allen in an interview, said  \"I believe in [[due process]]...I think these things really need to go through all the legal processes before anyone can judge. I don\u2019t really have an answer to those questions.\"<ref>Macnab, Geoffrey. (February 19, 2018) [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/emily-mortimer-interview-the-bookshop-woody-allen-mary-poppins-returns-jane-banks-disney-john-a8217661.html \"Emily Mortimer Interview\"]. ''[[The Independent]]''. Retrieved March 16, 2018.</ref> [[Jeff Daniels]], when asked if he would work with Allen again, responded: \"I believe Dylan Farrow. Would I do another one with Woody? The difficult decision would be to turn him down, because of ''[[The Purple Rose of Cairo]]''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2018/02/jeff-daniels-woody-allen-difficult-decision-1201933381/|title=Jeff Daniels Believes Dylan Farrow But Says Turning Down Woody Allen Would be a 'Difficult Decision'|website=[[Indiewire.com]]|first=Zack|last=Sharf|date=February 27, 2018|accessdate=March 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.com/movies/jeff-daniels-woody-allens-legacy-big-asterisk-would-consider-working-with-him/|title=Jeff Daniels Says Woody Allen's Legacy Now Has a 'Big Asterisk'|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|first=Mike|last=Miller|date=March 9, 2018|accessdate=March 10, 2018}}</ref> In February 2018, Savanah Lyon, a theater major at the [[University of California, San Diego]], began organising an online petition to have a course teaching Allen's films removed from the UCSD syllabus. Lyon stated that because of the abuse allegations against him, the university should not have a class devoted to studying Allen's work. On February 16, the UCSD Academic Senate announced that they were going to retain the course on Allen's work, stating that the removal of courses featuring \"controversial material, or even material widely regarded as morally problematic\" would undermine the values of free inquiry and [[academic freedom]].<ref>Flaherty, Collen.(February 26th, 2018.[https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/02/26/uc-san-diego-academic-senate-rejects-student-led-push-cut-course-woody-allen \"Woody Allen and Academic Freedom\"]. Retrieved 3 April 2018.</ref> [[Cate Blanchett]], when asked about the allegations against Allen by [[Christiane Amanpour]], replied \"At the time, I said it\u2019s a very painful and complicated situation for the family, which I hope they have the ability to resolve.\" Blanchett added: \"If these allegations need to be re-examined which, in my understanding, they\u2019ve been through court, then I\u2019m a big believer in the justice system and setting legal precedents,....If the case needs to be reopened, I am absolutely, wholeheartedly in support of that.\"<ref>Telegraph Reporters, (22 March 2018).[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2018/03/23/cate-blanchett-denies-staying-silent-metoo-working-woody-allen/ \"Cate Blanchett denies 'staying silent' on #MeToo while working with Woody Allen\".] ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''. Retrieved 3 April 2018.</ref> [[Javier Bardem]] stated: \"I am very shocked by this sudden treatment. Judgements in the states of New York and Connecticut found him innocent. The legal situation today is the same as in 2007. If there was evidence Woody Allen was guilty, then yes, I would have stopped working with him, but I have doubts.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/apr/19/javier-bardem-defends-woody-allen-i-am-very-shocked-by-this-treatment|title=Javier Bardem defends Woody Allen: 'I am very shocked by this treatment'|website=[[The Guardian]]|first=Guardian|last=Staff|date=April 19, 2018|accessdate=November 9, 2018}}</ref> Bardem in another interview stated: \"\u201cIf the legal situation ever changes [regarding Allen], then I\u2019d change my mind. But for now I don\u2019t agree with the public lynching that he\u2019s been receiving, and if Woody Allen called me to work with him again, I\u2019d be there tomorrow morning. He\u2019s a genius.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/10/javier-bardem-woody-allen-opinion|title=Javier Bardem Calls Woody Allen Backlash a \"Public Lynching\"|website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|first=Yohanna|last=Desta|date=October 19, 2018|accessdate=November 9, 2018}}</ref> [[Alan Alda]] stated \"I'd work with him again if he wanted me. I'm not qualified to judge him. I don't know all the facts. I don't know if he's guilty or innocent. But you can be uncertain \u2014 that's what I go on. I just don't have enough information to convince me I shouldn't work with him. And he's an enormously talented guy.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/alan-alda-mash-legacy-why-hed-work-woody-allen-again-1178289|title=Alan Alda on 'M*A*S*H' Legacy and Why He'd Work With Woody Allen Again|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Benjamin|last=Svetkey|date=January 25, 2019|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}</ref> [[Michael Caine]], who initially expressed regret for working with Allen and said he would never work with him again, later stated: \"If he had a trial and someone proved he had done something, I wouldn\u2019t do it. No. But I didn\u2019t read of him being on trial and being found guilty or fined or sent to prison or anything. This is all things that people say. You can\u2019t go on hearsay the whole time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/global/michael-caine-woody-allen-1202723613/|title=Michael Caine: I Won't Work With Woody Allen Again|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Leo|last=Barraclough|date=March 11, 2018|accessdate=March 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/michael-caine-interview-winston-churchill-jack-nicholson-beatles-778058/|title=The Last Word: Michael Caine on the First Time He Got High and the Role He Regrets Most|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|first=David|last=Browne|date=January 22, 2019|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref> [[Jeff Goldblum]] stated \"I think there is a presumption of innocence until proven guilty, I also admire his body of work. So I would consider working with him again, until I learned something more.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/11/08/jeff-goldblum-says-would-consider-working-with-woody-allen-again/|title=Jeff Goldblum said he would consider working with Woody Allen again, and the Internet is not okay|website=[[The Washington Post]]|first=Allyson|last=Chiu|date=November 8, 2019|accessdate=November 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMoses Farrow wrote an extensive blog post accusing Mia Farrow of emotionally abusing her children and driving some to suicide: \"Most media sources claim my sister Tam died of 'heart failure' at the age of 21. In fact, Tam struggled with depression for much of her life, a situation exacerbated by my mother refusing to get her help, insisting that Tam was just 'moody.' One afternoon in 2000, after one final fight with Mia, which ended with my mother leaving the house, Tam committed suicide by overdosing on pills.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.mamamia.com.au/moses-mia-farrow-children-woody-allen/|title='There was a darkness within our family.' The complex and tragic story of Mia Farrow's 14 children|first=Clare|last=Stephens|publisher=[[Mamamia (website)|Mamamia]]|location=Australia|date=May 28, 2018|accessdate=June 9, 2018|archivedate=May 28, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180528141514/https://www.mamamia.com.au/moses-mia-farrow-children-woody-allen/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=MosesFarrowMay2018 /> His sister Soon-Yi had written similarly in 1992, saying in a statement, \"Mia was always very hot-tempered and given to rages which terrified all the kids. They can't speak freely because they're still dependent on her. But they could really tell stories and I'm sure one day will. It's true Mia was violent with me and I have conclusive proof, but I hope she and Woody can somehow head off a custody trial.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/soon-yi-speaks-lets-not-get-hysterical-197958| title=Soon-Yi Speaks: 'Let's Not Get Hysterical'|work=[[Newsweek]]|date=August 30, 1992|accessdate=June 9, 2018| archivedate=April 13, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413120034/http://www.newsweek.com/soon-yi-speaks-lets-not-get-hysterical-197958|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Woody Allen memoirs \"Apropos of nothing.\" ===\nIn his memoir, Woody Allen addresses Dylan's allegation of abuse. He explains that, unlike other cases of sexual abuse or harassment that could have been ignored without being taken seriously or adequately investigated, Mia Farrow's accusation against him was taken with the utmost seriousness and was immediately and thoroughly investigated by two groups of different experts.\n\nOn the one hand, the police and the prosecution hired the most prestigious experts in the country: the Child Sexual Abuse Clinic at the Yale-New Haven Hospital, whom the police used to look into such matters and who concluded that the evidence conclusively proved that there was not sexual abuse, that Dylan\u00b4s statements had \"a rehearsed quality\" and were likely \"coached or influenced by her mother. \" Regarding the criticism against Yale New haven for having destroyed the original notes at the time of incorporating them into the report, Allen reveals that in the course of the trial it turned out that it was the usual procedure of both Yale New Haven and the FBI to preserve privacy\n\nOn the other hand, the New York State Child Welfare scrupulously investigated the case for 14 months and concluded that there was no credible evidence of abuse and that the allegation was unfounded.\n\nAllen recounts a session of the Yale-New Haven investigation during which Mia Farrow explained to experts how Dylan was so disturbed by the sexual abuse that she immediately rushed to her sister Lark's room for comfort. Farrow described how Dylan hugged Lark and how Lark comforted her. When Allen noted that Lark was in New York on the day the abuse was alleged to have happened and there was no way Dylan would have come to her, hugged her, and Lark comfort her, Mia Farrow changed her account and said that \"\" Lark was in New York at the time, but Dylan hugged her spiritually. \" Allen concluded that while Mia Farrow's story may have had some impact on the judges, it did not mislead investigators.\n\nRegarding the investigation conducted by Connecticut prosecutor Frank Maco, Allen indicates that from the moment the experts the prosecution had hired totally rejected the possibility of sexual abuse, the prosecution's investigation should have been closed. That it was kept open without any justification and that this fact was in favor of Farrow during the custody trial, that the statement at the prosecutor's press conference saying that there was probable cause was totally unfounded once the prosecution experts had already completely ruled out the possibility of sexual abuse. Allen points out that it is absurd to think that the prosecutor did not initiate prosecution becouse he did not want to hurt Dylan when he had police question Dylan for months without caring at all about Dylan's well-being. Allen also indicates that a nanny and a housekeeper who worked at Mia Farrow's house stated that on multiple occasions the prosecutor \u00a0showed up by the house and he and Mia Farrow went out to luch. Allen \u00a0regrets that this does not seem the most appropriate way conducting an impartial investigation.\n\nAllan also says that in the custody trial, the Court Clerk drove Mia Farrow to her home from the courthose many nigths and thinks it was a \u00a0\u201cunfair conduit to the judge\u201d, recalls the testimony by Moses Farrow, who said he witnessed how Mia Farrow coached Dylan to say that she had been abused, collects the testimony of a babysitter to whom Dylan said \"Mummy want me to lie.\" Allen says that long before the allegation of abuse emerged Mia Farrow took Dylan to a child therapist because the girl had trouble distinguishing between reality and fantasy. The girl who under normal conditions had trouble distinguishing reality from fantasy was at the exclusive care of her mother during a strong and confusing emotional crisis Farrow suggested the child that she had been abused, which ended up leading to Dylan sincerely believed it.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Allen, Woody.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1147948052|title=Apropos of Nothing|isbn=978-1-951627-34-8|oclc=1147948052}}</ref>\n\n\n\n<br />\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|26em}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite news|last1=Hoban|first1=Phoebe|title=Woody and Mia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3uQCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA40|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=September 21, 1992|pages=32\u201342}}\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/04/nyregion/doctor-cites-inconsistencies-in-dylan-farrow-s-statements.html Doctor Cites Inconsistencies In Dylan Farrow's Statements], The New York Times, May 4, 1993\n* [http://articles.latimes.com/1993-02-02/news/mn-952_1_woody-allen Nanny Casts Doubt on Farrow Charges : Custody: She tells Allen's lawyers the actress pressured her to support molestation accusations against him. She says others have reservations], Los Angeles Times, February 2, 1993\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/26/nyregion/agency-drops-abuse-inquiry-in-allen-case.html Agency Drops Abuse Inquiry in Allen Case], The New York Times, October 26, 1993\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Allen, Woody}}\n[[Category:1990s in the United States]]\n[[Category:Entertainment scandals]]\n[[Category:Sexual misconduct allegations]]\n[[Category:Woody Allen]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Dylan Farrow's accusations of Woody Allen sexually abusing her}}\nIn August 1992, the American film director [[Woody Allen]] was accused by his adoptive daughter Dylan Farrow, then 7 years old, of having sexually molested her in the home of her adoptive mother, the actress [[Mia Farrow]], in [[Bridgewater, Connecticut]].<ref name=OrthNov1992/> Allen has repeatedly denied the allegation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/woody-allen-defends-himself-on-60-minutes-in-92/|title=Woody Allen defends himself on '60 Minutes' in '92|publisher=[[CBS News]]|accessdate= February 8, 2018|archivedate=November 22, 2014| archiveurl=https://archive.is/VNhj0|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=AllenFeb72014/>\n\nWhen the allegation was made, Mia Farrow and Allen had been in a 12-year relationship and had three children together: two adopted children, Dylan and Moses, and one biological son, Satchel (now known as [[Ronan Farrow]]).<ref name=OrthNov1992/> The molestation is alleged to have taken place eight months after Farrow learned that Allen had been having an affair with another of her adoptive daughters, [[Soon-Yi Previn]], who married Allen in 1997; Previn was a first-year undergraduate and 21 years old when Farrow found out about the relationship.<ref name=Wypijewski26Feb2014/> Allen alleged that the affair prompted Mia Farrow to concoct the molestation allegation as an act of vengeance.<ref name=AllenFeb72014/> The Connecticut [[State's Attorney]] investigated the allegation but did not press charges,<ref name=Henneberger25Sept1993/> the Connecticut State Police referred Dylan to the Child\nSexual Abuse Clinic of\u00a0Yale\u2013New\u00a0Haven Hospital who concluded that Woody Allen had not sexually abused Dylan<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> and the New York Department of Social Services found \"no credible evidence\" to support the allegation.<ref name=PerezPena26Oct1993/> In response to the allegation, Allen sued Farrow for sole custody of Dylan, Satchel and Moses.<ref name=Weber14Aug1992/> He lost the case in June 1993; the judge concluded that the allegation of sexual abuse had not been proven.<ref name=\":0\">{{citation |first=Elliott|last= Wilk|publisher=Supreme Court: New York County |title=Custody Court Ruling}}</ref> Visitations with Dylan were suspended for six months until the girl recovered from what she had suffered so far,<ref>{{citation |first=Elliott|last= Wilk|publisher=Supreme Court: New York County  |title=Custody Case Ruling |date=July 6, 1993}}</ref> gave him limited, supervised visitation with Satchel, and allowed Moses, a teenager, to decide for himself.<ref name=Marks8June1993/><ref name=Shea7Feb2014/> The decision was upheld on appeal in 1994<ref name=appeal1994/> and 1995.<ref name=appeal1995/>\n\nDylan Farrow has repeated the allegation several times as an adult, although with important modifications with respect to the original narration of 1992 as it was described by Mia Farrow.<ref>{{Cite book|title=What Falls Away : A Memoir|first=Mia|last=Farrow|isbn=9781984800114|pages=299|oclc=1035846541|date=2018-05-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/dylan-farrow-interview-today-gayle-king-full-transcript-woody-allen-me-too/|title=Dylan Farrow details her sexual molestation allegations against Woody Allen|last=January 18|first=CBS News|last2=2018|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-22|last3=Am|first3=7:20}}</ref> Her first public comment was in an interview with [[Maureen Orth]] for ''Vanity Fair'' in 2013,<ref name=OrthOct2013/> followed by an open letter in the<!--CMOS 8.170--> ''New York Times'' in 2014,<ref name=Farrow1Feb2014/> and a ''Los Angeles Times'' [[op-ed]] in December 2017.<ref name=Farrow7Dec2017/> Woody Allen has also spoken publicly about the allegations, in an interview with [[Gayle King]] for ''[[CBS This Morning]]'', in  a ''New York Times'' op-ed<ref name=AllenFeb72014/> and in 2018 with a statement to CBS \u2013 each time denying the allegation.<ref name=CBS2018re>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/woody-allen-responds-dylan-farrow-sexual-abuse-allegations/|title=Woody responds to Dylan Farrow sexual abuse allegations|date=January 18, 2018|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n===Allen and Farrow===\nWoody Allen and Mia Farrow began a 12-year relationship in 1980, during which Farrow starred in 13 of Allen's films.<ref name=OrthOct2013>{{cite news|url= https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2013/11/mia-farrow-frank-sinatra-ronan-farrow| title=Momma Mia!| first=Maureen|last=Orth|author-link=Maureen Orth|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]| date= October 23, 2013}}</ref> They maintained separate apartments in [[Manhattan]] throughout the relationship\u2014Farrow on [[Central Park West]]<ref name=Smith8May1994/> and Allen on [[Fifth Avenue]]\u2014and did not marry; they had both been married twice.<ref name=Lax24Feb1991/>\n\n[[File:Mia Farrow 2012 Shankbone.JPG|thumb|upright|[[Mia Farrow]], 2012]]\nWhen the relationship began, Farrow had seven children: three biological sons from her marriage to composer [[Andr\u00e9 Previn]]; three adopted girls (two Vietnamese and one Korean, [[Soon-Yi Previn]]); and one adopted Korean boy, Moses.<ref name=Lax24Feb1991>{{cite news | title=Woody and Mia: A New York Story |first=Eric|last=Lax|work=The New York Times|date=February 24, 1991|url= https://www.nytimes.com/1991/02/24/magazine/woody-and-mia-a-new-york-story.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Woody Allen, Mia Farrow family tree|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/02/03/showbiz/gallery/allen-farrow-family-tree/index.html|publisher=CNN|date=May 11, 2016}}</ref> In July 1985 she adopted a baby girl, Dylan, from Texas. Allen was not involved in the adoption, but when Dylan arrived he assumed a parental role toward her and began spending more time in Farrow's home. He and Farrow went on holiday to Europe several times with the Farrow\u2013Previn children between 1987 and 1989, although the judicial investigation concluded that \"He remained aloof from Ms. Farrow's other children except for Moses, to whom he was cordial.\"<ref name=Stern10Feb2014>{{cite news|last1=Stern|first1=Marlow|title=Inside the Shocking Custody Case Court Documents that Shed Light on the Dylan Farrow-Woody Allen Saga|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/inside-the-shocking-custody-case-court-documents-that-shed-light-on-the-dylan-farrow-woody-allen-saga|work=The Daily Beast|date=February 10, 2014}}</ref> In December 1987 Farrow gave birth to Allen's biological son, Satchel (later known as [[Ronan Farrow]]).<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1987/12/22/arts/son-born-to-mia-farrow-and-woody-allen.html | title = Son Born to Mia Farrow And Woody Allen | agency = Associated Press |newspaper=The New York Times | date= December 22, 1987}}</ref> Farrow wanted to adopt another child in 1991; Allen said he would not take \"a lousy attitude toward it\" so long as she agreed to his adoption of Dylan and Moses,<ref name=Stern10Feb2014/> and in October that year she adopted another Vietnamese child.{{efn|Farrow found that the child was too disabled and needed more care than she could provide; she helped to find him another family.<ref name=Smith8May1994>{{cite news|last1=Dinitia|first1=Smith|title=Picking Up The Legos And The Pieces|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/02/23/reviews/farrow-feature.html|work=The New York Times|date=May 8, 1994}}</ref>}} Allen's adoption of Dylan and Moses was finalized on December 17, 1991.<ref name=Stern10Feb2014/>\n\n{{external media\n| float  = left\n| width  = 230px\n| image1 = [https://web.archive.org/web/20180122001118/https://imagesvc.timeincapp.com/v3/mm/image?url=http%3A%2F%2Fpeoplev6.alley.ws%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2016%2F08%2Fwoody-allen-01-600.jpg On holiday, Leningrad, 1987]<br/>''Left to right'': [[Ronan Farrow|Ronan]], Lark, Woody Allen, Dylan, Fletcher, Daisy, [[Soon-Yi Previn]], Moses, and Mia Farrow.\n| image2 = [http://images.nymag.com/news/features/scandals/scandals120409_1992_560.jpg Allen, Farrow and Soon-Yi Previn], c.&nbsp;1987.\n}}\nAccording to her testimony during the custody trial, Farrow became concerned about Allen's behavior around Dylan in 1987\u20131988. She reportedly told Allen that he was paying too much attention to Dylan and failing to give her \"breathing room\". He had allegedly read to Dylan while in his underwear, allowed her to suck his thumb, and would sit on her bed in the morning waiting for her to wake up.<ref name=Stern10Feb2014/><ref name=Marks27March1993/><ref name=OrthNov1992/> Farrow would later testify that she found Allen's relationship with Dylan at this time \"relentless and overpowering\", and said it had \"a wooing quality\";<ref name=\"wmr\">[https://www.upi.com/Archives/1993/03/25/Mia-I-worried-about-Woody-being-a-homosexual/8544733035600/ \"Mia: I worried about Woody being a homosexual\"]. William M. Reilly, March 25, 1993. [[UPI.com]]. Retrieved 14 October 2018.</ref> however, in 1990 Mia Farrow changed her will so that in the event of her death the care and custody of her minor children (Dylan, Satchel and Moses) would be left to Allen.<ref>{{Cite book|title=What Falls Away:a memoir|last=Farrow|first=Mia|publisher=Doubleday|year=1997|isbn=0-385-47187-4|location=New York|pages=249 }}</ref> Furthermore, in 1991, she made an affidavit to the judge promoting the adoption of Dylan and Moses by Allen, praising especially the qualities of Allen as Dylan's father: \"Mr. Allen is a loving, caring, attentive parent to Dylan and she can only benefit from having him as an adoptive father\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1993/01/12/More-bombshells-dropped-at-Woody-Allen-hearing/8879726814800/|title=More bombshells dropped at Woody Allen hearing|last=REILLY|first=M. William|date=Jan 12, 1993|website=UPI Archives|access-date=}}</ref> Farrow also told her therapist that she feared Woody \"would abuse Satchel\", and that she also worried that Allen had a sexual relationship \"with another man\".<ref name=\"wmr\" /> On one occasion, Dylan allegedly locked herself in the bathroom for four hours when he arrived; Allen had an employee pick the lock with a coat hanger.<ref name=Marks27March1993/> The family psychologist, Dr. Susan Coates, witnessed some of Allen's behavior and testified during the custody trial in 1993 that she did not see it as sexual, but as \"inappropriately intense because it excluded everybody else\".<ref name=Wypijewski26Feb2014/><ref name=Marks30March1993/> Allen said later that he had paid extra attention to Dylan to compensate for the time Farrow was spending with the newborn, Satchel.<ref name=appeal1994/> According to Maureen Orth, he agreed in 1990 to discuss the issue in therapy sessions;<ref name=OrthNov1992/> however, the therapist Dr. Coates, stated at the trial that Woody Allen was not in therapy with her and that both parents were part of the children's therapy. Woody Allen wanted to improve as a father, but he was not in therapy for inappropriate behaviors with Dylan.<ref>{{cite web |last1=L. Miller |first1=Tracy |title=Psychiatrist: Woody was committed to being a good father |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1993/03/30/Psychiatrist-Woody-was-committed-to-being-a-good-father/1405733467600/ |website=UPI |access-date=March 30, 1990}}</ref>\n\n===Relationship with Previn===\nIn 1991 Allen began an affair with Farrow's adopted daughter Soon-Yi Previn. According to Allen, it began in late December 1991.<ref name=PerezPena23March1993/> In August 1992 Mia Farrow told her lawyer, Alan Dershowitz, that Soon Yi had acknowledged by talking to her that the relationship between Allen and Soon Yi had begun on December 1, 1991.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=NEW YORK DAILY NEWS Easter Season Poll, 1986|last=Hackett|first=Larry|date=1988-06-01|page=5|doi = 10.3886/icpsr08584}}</ref> Later she said it began while Previn was in her final year of high school, which ended in June 1991. She alleged that Dylan saw Allen and Previn on the bed together in the summer or autumn of 1991.<ref name=Marks27March1993>{{cite news|last1=Marks|first1=Peter|title=Farrow Says Daughter Became Distraught Over Allen's Relentless Attention|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/02/23/reviews/farrow-trial.html|work=The New York Times|date=March 27, 1993}}</ref> The appeal Court Ruling found that the sexual relationship between Allen and Soon Yi began in December 1991.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Appellate Division of the Supreme Court of the State of New York, First Department. |title=Woody Allen, Appellant, v. Maria V. Farrow, Also Known as Mia Farrow, Respondent |date=May 12, 1994 |volume=197 A.D.2d 327 (1994) }}</ref> One point of contention has been how old Previn was at the time. When Farrow and Andr\u00e9 Previn adopted her from [[Seoul]] in 1977, the Seoul family court gave her a legal birth document  with a presumptive birth date of October 8, 1970; she had been abandoned and was living in that city's St. Paul's Orphanage.{{efn|\"Information concerning this case was obtained from Mr. and Mrs. Andr\u00e9 G. Previn&nbsp;... The beneficiary, Soon Hee Oh, aka Soon Yi Oh, is a native and citizen of Korea with a presumptive birth date of October 8, 1970.\"<ref>United States Congressional Serial Set, Issue 13173, 1977, p.&nbsp;[https://books.google.com/books?id=1TYoAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Soon+Hee+Oh,+aka+Soon+Yi+Oh%22 170].</ref> \"Memorandum of information concerning H.R. 1352 for the relief of Oh Soon Hee submitted by the American Embassy at Seoul, Korea. The beneficiary is an abandoned child, who was found in Seoul, Korea on February 12, 1976. She was placed temporarily in the care of Maria's House, a local institution for abandoned children while an effort was made to identify and locate her parents and relatives. When this search failed, the beneficiary was transferred to the care of St. Paul's Orphanage&nbsp;... in Seoul, where she currently lives. The Seoul Family Court established a Family Census Register (legal birth document) in her behalf on December 28, 1976, with a presumptive birth date of October 8, 1970. The beneficiary attends kindergarten classes held in the orphanage. Through the auspices of the Social Welfare Society, Inc.,&nbsp;... and the Friends of Children adoption agency in the United States, the child has been selected for adoption by Mr. and Mrs. Andr\u00e9 George Previn, of Martha's Vineyard, Mass.&nbsp;...<ref>United States Congressional Serial Set, 1978, p.&nbsp;[https://books.google.com/books?id=UPBIAQAAMAAJ&dq=%22Soon-Yi%22+Previn+%22October+8%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22October+8%22 cxlii\u2013cxliv].</ref>}} According to Farrow, the family regarded her date of birth as October 8, 1972,<ref name=Wypijewski26Feb2014/> although the first reaction of the nanny Kristi Groteke when in May 1992 Mia Farrow told her that Woody Allen had had a relationship with Soon Yi was to remember that she was a 21-year-old woman.<ref>{{cite book|title=Mia & Woody. Love and betrayal|last1=Groteke|first1=Kristi|last2=Rosen|first2=Marjorie|publisher=Carroll & Graf Publishers, Inc.|year=1994|isbn=0-7867-0066-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/miawoodylovebetr00grot/page/79 79]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/miawoodylovebetr00grot/page/79}}</ref> The timing of the affair became an issue in part because Farrow attempted, unsuccessfully, to have Allen's adoption of Dylan and Moses declared void after the molestation allegation, on the grounds that his affair with Previn had begun before the adoptions were finalized on December 17, 1991.<ref name=Perez19June1993/>\n\n[[File:Soon Yi Previn and Woody Allen at the Tribeca Film Festival.jpg|thumb|left|[[Soon-Yi Previn]] and [[Woody Allen]], 2009]]\nDuring her final year of high school, Previn told Allen that she wanted to be a model; he advised her how to dress and arranged for professional photographs to be taken.<ref name=OrthNov1992/> She reportedly asked if she could accompany him to a basketball game, and after attending several together, they became closer.<ref name=Isaacson31Aug1992>{{cite news|last1=Isaacson|first1=Walter|title=The Heart Wants What It Wants|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,160439,00.html|work=Time|date=June 24, 2001|at=First published August 31, 1992}}</ref><ref name=Stern10Feb2014/> Their affair came to light on January 13, 1992, when Farrow found nude [[Instant camera|Polaroid]] photographs of Previn on the [[Fireplace mantel|mantel]] in Allen's home.<ref name=Wypijewski26Feb2014/><ref name=Perez20March1993/> Previn was by then in her first year at [[Drew University]] in New Jersey.<ref name=OrthNov1992/> Allen, then 56, told Farrow that he had taken the photographs the day before, and that he and Previn had first had sex in the last week of December 1991.<ref name=PerezPena23March1993>{{cite news|last1=Perez-Pena|first1=Richard|title=Nude Photographs Are Focus Of Woody Allen's Testimony|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/03/23/nyregion/nude-photographs-are-focus-of-woody-allen-s-testimony.html|work=The New York Times|date=March 23, 1993}}</ref><ref name=Perez19June1993/> Allen told the custody trial in 1993 that he regarded the images as erotic, but not pornographic; the appellate court said that it did not \"share Mr. Allen's characterization\" of the photographs.<ref name=appeal1994/>\n\nAlthough the discovery shocked the family, Farrow did not stop Allen from visiting her home,<ref name=OrthOct2013/> and she completed her work on ''[[Husbands and Wives]]'' (1992), the last film of his in which she appeared.<ref name=Grimes31Aug1992>{{cite news|last1=Grimes|first1=William|title=A Chronology of a Film's Making And a Relationship's Unmaking|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/08/31/movies/a-chronology-of-a-film-s-making-and-a-relationship-s-unmaking.html|work=The New York Times|date=August 31, 1992}}</ref><ref name=Barron21Aug1992>{{cite news|last1=Barron|first1=James|title=Plot of New Woody Allen Film Seems to Mimic His Life|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/08/21/nyregion/plot-of-new-woody-allen-film-seems-to-mimic-his-life.html|work=The New York Times|date=August 21, 1992}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=James|first1=Caryn|title=Film View; And Here We Thought We Knew Him|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/09/06/movies/film-view-and-here-we-thought-we-knew-him.html|work=The New York Times|date=September 6, 1992}}</ref> According to Farrow, Allen said his relationship with Previn was over;<ref name=OrthOct2013/> she alleged that Allen asked her to issue a joint press release, in response to rumors about the relationship, in which she would confirm there was nothing between Allen and Previn, but she refused to do it.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Farrow|first1=Mia|title=What Falls Away|date=1997|publisher=Bantam|location=New York|page=269|ref=harv}}</ref> She was hurt and angry,<ref name=Marks30March1993/> but nevertheless adopted two more children that month: Tam, a blind Vietnamese girl, and Isaiah Justus, an African-American baby boy.<ref name=OrthNov1992/>\n\nAllen and Previn remained in contact; in July 1992 she lost her job as a summer-camp counselor in Maine after spending too much time on the telephone with a \"Mr. Simon\", who turned out to be Allen.<ref name=Stern10Feb2014/> Allen says that when he visited Connecticut to celebrate Dylan's birthday, Farrow left a note on a door in which she called him a \"child molester\".<ref>\"Allen Said Farrow Made Good On Her Promise\". [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1314&dat=19921123&id=orwzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PPADAAAAIBAJ&pg=1660,2745737&hl=en] ''[[The Spokesman-Review]]'', November 23rd, 1992. (p.1) Retrieved 14 October 2018.</ref> On 1 August 1992, according to the testimony of Dr. Susan Coates, Farrow telephoned Dr. Coates to say she had learned that Previn and Allen were still in a relationship; Farrow was distressed and told Coates that, just a week earlier, she and Allen had talked about getting married; \"Ms. Farrow described Mr. Allen as \"satanic and evil,\" Dr. Coates said, adding that Ms. Farrow pleaded with her to \"find a way to stop him.\"<ref name=Marks30March1993/> Allen publicly announced his relationship with Previn on 17 August 1992. Soon Yi said later that month that Woody Allen had never been a father figure to her, and that they had become friendly only after his romance with Mia Farrow had ended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/soon-yi-speaks-lets-not-get-hysterical-197958|title=Soon-Yi Speaks: 'Let's Not Get Hysterical'|last=EDT|first=Newsweek Staff On 8/30/92 at 8:00 PM|date=1992-08-30|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> As Allen and Mia Farrow had never married, and as Allen had never adopted Soon-Yi, their relationship was not illegal.<ref>[https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/137176042?searchTerm=jack%20waterford%20%22soon-yi%22%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20&searchLimits= \"Modern Reasons For Old Taboos on Incest\".] Jack Waterford, ''[[The Canberra Times]]''. 27 August 1992 (p 9) Retrieved 14th October 2018.</ref> Previn and Allen's relationship did continue, and they were married in Venice on December 23, 1997.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Collins|first1=Glenn|title=Mixed Reviews Greet Woody Allen Marriage| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/12/25/nyregion/mixed-reviews-greet-woody-allen-marriage.html|work=The New York Times|date=December 25, 1997}}</ref>\n\n==Allegation==\nOn August 4, 1992, Allen visited his children at Farrow's country home in Bridgewater, Connecticut, while Farrow and a friend went shopping with the two most recently adopted children, Tam and Isaiah.<ref name=OrthNov1992 /> Farrow and Allen had been due to sign an agreement on August 6, that Allen would pay $6,000 a month for the support of Dylan, Satchel and Moses;<ref name=OrthNov1992/> although Martin Weltz, lawyer of Mia Farrow, said that on August 4 Mia Farrow called him on the phone, to suspend the processing of the agreement.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3uQCAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Everything You Always Wanted to Know About Woody and Mia (But Were Afraid to Ask)|last=Hoban|first=Phoebe|date=September 21, 1992|website=Books Google|publisher=New York Magazine|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nPresent in the house once Farrow had left, were: Dylan; Satchel; Farrow's babysitter, Kristie Groteke; the children's French tutor, Sophie Berge; Farrow's friend's three children; and Farrow's friend's babysitter, Alison Strickland. When Mia Farrow left the house Moses was, according to her, \"off by himself taking a walk\". Moses claimed he was already in the house when Allen arrived.{{sfnp|Farrow|1997|p=270}}<ref name=\"MosesFarrowMay2018\" /> The day after the visit, Stickland told her employer that she had seen Allen kneel on the floor in front of Dylan, then aged seven, with his face in her lap turned toward Dylan's body; she testified to that effect during the custody trial.<ref name=MarksApril101993>{{cite news|last1=Marks|first1=Peter|title=Sitter Questions Allen Actions With Daughter|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/04/10/nyregion/sitter-questions-allen-actions-with-daughter.html|work=The New York Times|date=April 10, 1993}}</ref> (The judge, after hearing the full testimony of Alison Strickland, did not believe that she was describing any kind of abuse or inappropriate behavior) <ref name=\"Shea7Feb2014\" /> Farrow asked Dylan about it, Dylan allegedly described what had happened and said she had not liked it; Farrow telephoned her attorney for guidance and was advised to take Dylan to her local pediatrician. Farrow took Dylan to Dr. Vadakkekara Kavirajan, the regular paediatrician for Farrow's children, where the girl did not make any allegation of abuse.\n\nAccording to the expert hired by Farrow, Farrow had videotaped Dylan's answers to her questions prior to the visit to the pediatrician in which Dylan made the allegation of abuse   \"in fits and starts\", and in a way that \"set a tone for a child about how to answer\",<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mia & Woody : love and betrayal|first=Kristi|last=Groteke|date=1994|publisher=Carroll & Graf|isbn=|pages=169|oclc=1036704501}}</ref> and Dylan told Farrow&nbsp;that she&nbsp;had been with&nbsp;Mr.&nbsp;Allen&nbsp;in&nbsp;the attic,<ref>{{harvnb|Farrow|1997|p=272}}; {{cite news|title=Woody Allen claims videotape proves Mia's 'unfitness' as mother|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1992/12/21/Woody-Allen-claims-videotape-proves-Mias-unfitness-as-mother/4450724914000/|publisher=UPI|date=December 21, 1992}}</ref> and&nbsp;that he had touched&nbsp;her private parts.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thunderpeel2001.com/files/Allen-v-Farrow.pdf|title=Allen v. Farrow (1993)|last=Wilk|first=Elliott, J.|website=|access-date= }}</ref><ref name=Stern10Feb2014/><ref name=OrthNov1992>{{cite news |last=Orth|first=Maureen|author-link=Maureen Orth|title=Mia's Story|magazine=Vanity Fair|date=August 5, 2008|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/archive/1992/11/farrow199211|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221205817/http://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/archive/1992/11/farrow199211|archive-date=November 1992|url-status=live}}</ref> On day six, they returned to the pediatrician where Dylan repeated the allegation; Dr. Kavirajan then informed authorities, although he said he found no physical evidence of sexual molestation.{{sfnp|Farrow|1997|p=272}}<ref name=\"Orth7Feb2014\">{{cite web|last1=Orth|first1=Maureen|title=10 Undeniable Facts About the Woody Allen Sexual-Abuse Allegation|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2014/02/woody-allen-sex-abuse-10-facts|website=Vanity Fair|date=7 February 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"fmw\">[https://www.upi.com/Archives/1992/08/19/Woody-Abuse-charge-video-tape-forced-him-to-seek-childrens-custody/5213714196800/ \"Woody: Abuse charge, video tape forced him to seek children's custody\"] Frederick M Winship. August 19th, 1992. UPI. Retrieved 14 October 2018.</ref> Dr. Kavirajan would later tell an interviewer that he was \"required by state law\" to report any allegations of child abuse.<ref name=\"fmw\" /> Dr. Susan Coates informed Allen of the allegation during one of the sessions in which he was participating in Satchel's therapy; he responded \"I'm completely flabbergasted,\" repeating it several times.<ref name=\"Marks30March1993\" />\n\n==Legal action==\n===Custody proceedings and statements===\nOn August 13, 1992, a week after being told about the allegation, Allen began proceedings in [[New York Supreme Court]] for sole custody of Dylan, Moses, and his and Farrow's biological son, Satchel.<ref name=Weber14Aug1992>{{cite news|last1=Weber|first1=Bruce|title=Woody Allen Files Child-Custody Lawsuit|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/08/14/nyregion/woody-allen-files-child-custody-lawsuit.html|work=The New York Times|date=August 14, 1992}}</ref> Farrow's mother, the actor [[Maureen O'Sullivan]], issued a statement on August 15 that was critical of Allen and said that Farrow had retained [[Alan Dershowitz]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rabinovitz|first1=Jonathan|title=War! Mia Fights Back With (Gasp!) Publicity|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/08/16/nyregion/war-mia-fights-back-with-gasp-publicity.html|work=The New York Times|date=August 16, 1992}}</ref> Two days later, Allen released his first public comment about his relationship with Soon-Yi Previn: \"Regarding my love for Soon-Yi: It's real and happily all true. She's a lovely, intelligent, sensitive woman who has and continues to turn around my life in a wonderfully positive way.\"<ref name=Weber18Aug1992>{{cite news|last1=Weber|first1=Bruce|title=Public Disclosures From the Private Life of Woody Allen|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/08/18/nyregion/public-disclosures-from-the-private-life-of-woody-allen.html|work=The New York Times|date=August 18, 1992}}</ref><ref name=Wilkinson11Jan2018>{{cite news|last1=Wilkinson|first1=Alissa|title=Why Woody Allen hasn't been toppled by the #MeToo reckoning \u2014 yet|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2018/1/11/16635446/woody-allen-dylan-farrow-mia-ronan-sexual-molestation-allegation-metoo|work=Vox|date=January 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn August 18 Allen held a news conference at the [[Plaza Hotel]]. Calling the molestation allegation \"an unconscionable and gruesomely damaging manipulation of innocent children for vindictive and self-serving motives,\" he alleged that, during a meeting on August 13, Farrow's lawyers had demanded $5\u20138 million hush money.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Marks|first1=Peter|title=Dershowitz Says Farrow Involved Him|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/04/16/nyregion/dershowitz-says-farrow-involved-him.html|work=The New York Times|date=August 16, 1992}}</ref><ref name=Barron19Aug1992>{{cite news|last1=Barron|first1=James|title=Striking Back, Woody Allen Denies Child Sex-Abuse Allegation|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/08/19/nyregion/striking-back-woody-allen-denies-child-sex-abuse-allegation.html|work=The New York Times|date=August 19, 1992}}</ref> Dershowitz responded that the lawyers had suggested Allen pay a lump sum in child support, rather than a monthly one, to reduce Allen's interaction with Farrow. It would be $17,000 a month until each child reach the age of 21, $900,000 for College tuition and $2,500,000 for Mia Farrow herself as compensation for her loss of income for the next 10 years. Allen's lawyers declared that Farrow's proposal was that in exchange for the money she would drop the charges of sexual abuse, Dershowitz flatly denied this possibility and noted that he was trying to reach an agreement that would allow the matter not to be made public and convince the Connecticut police that it was best not to intervene and \"decriminalize\" the case, but that the proposal was completely separate and independent of the economic proposal. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1993/04/15/Dershowitz-Woody-is-on-the-road-to-ruin/2543734846400/|title=Dershowitz: Woody is on the road to ruin|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Barron|first1=James|title=Allen 'Spoiled and Mutilated' His Better Self, Farrow Says|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/08/20/nyregion/allen-spoiled-and-mutilated-his-better-self-farrow-says.html|work=The New York Times|date=August 20, 1992}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Goldman|first1=John J.|title=Final Arguments in Allen Custody Trial as Bitter as First|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-05-05/news/mn-31539_1_daughter-farrow|work=Los Angeles Times|date=May 5, 1993}}</ref> On August 20 Allen's publicist announced that Allen had passed a lie detector test.<ref name=Barron21Aug1992/> The following day, Allen gave an interview to [[Walter Isaacson]] of ''Time'' magazine, describing the nude photographs of Previn as a \"lark of a moment\". Of the affair, he said: \"I didn't feel that just because she was Mia's daughter, there was any great moral dilemma. It was a fact, but not one with any great import.\"<ref name=Isaacson31Aug1992/><ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|last1=Hevesi|first1=Dennis|title=Woody Allen Tells His Side to a Magazine|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/08/23/nyregion/woody-allen-tells-his-side-to-a-magazine.html|work=The New York Times|date=August 23, 1992}}</ref>\n\nDuring the fall of 1992, the police interviewed Dylan utilising anatomical dolls. The last of the interviews took place on December 30, 1992, during which Dylan inserted the penis of the male doll into the vagina of the female doll. When the police asked her why she knew that the dolls fit like that, she told them that during the summer her brother Satchel and she had witnessed how Woody Allen introduced his penis into Soon Yi's vagina. \"Daddies do not do this\" she told them, according to the statement, and \"daddies are not supposed to act like boyfriends.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mia & Woody : love and betrayal|first=Kristi|last=Groteke|date=1994|publisher=Carroll & Graf|isbn=|pages=172|oclc=1036704501 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Saw dad, Soon Yi in bed:Woody Kid|last=Hackett|first=Larry|date=1993-01-13|work=New York Daily News|access-date= }}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Dylan Saw It All 7-year-old says she watched Woody, Soon-Yi having sex|last=Kocieniewski|first=David|date=1993-01-13|work=Newsday|access-date=}}</ref>\nThis disclosure was made by Eleanor Alter in the course of the court hearing in which they treated the right of visits in favor of Woody Allen that would govern during the processing of the procedure. The session was suspended due to the seriousness of the allegation.\n\nThe Yale New Haven team had finished interviewing Dylan on November 13, 1992.<ref name=\":2\" /> One of the aspects they had explored was the relationship between boyfriends and girlfriends. In November 1992 that relationship consisted for Dylan in \"kisses and hugs.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Woody Says He's Cleared Report: No sign of sex abuse: Excerpts From the Yale Report|last=Polner|first=Rob|date=1993-03-19|work=Newsday|access-date= }}</ref> The judicial investigation concluded that the sexual relationship between Soon Yi and Allen began in December 1991.<ref name=\"appeal1994\" /> {{cl-span|Allen declared that the allegation that Dylan has witnessed a sexual relationship in summer was not true|date=November 2019|reason= what allegation? THe relationship was stated to start in december 1991 by Allen (prev section)}} because {{cl-span|it was months before his relationship with Soon Yi started|date=November 2019|reason=It? what is it? Also, Allen stated that dec 1991 was the start, so what the \"it\" that was \"months before\" that happened in july/august/september?}},<ref name=\":5\" /> and \"I think that when Mia needs something, she takes our daughter and makes her say it.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Lawyer:kids saw Woody, Soon Yi have sex|last=Associated Press|date=1993-01-13|work=Star-Gazette|page=2}}</ref>\n\nAllen and Farrow reached an agreement through which Allen would not begin visits with Dylan immediately in exchange for Mia Farrow providing a therapist to the child.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Woody & Mia OK shrink for Dylan|last=Hackett|first=Larry|date=1993-01-20|work=Daily News|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Yale\u2013New Haven Hospital team===\nOn August 17, 1992, the [[Connecticut State Police]] announced that they were investigating the molestation allegation.<ref name=Weber18Aug1992/><ref name=Wilkinson11Jan2018/> In September Dylan was referred to the Child Sexual Abuse Clinic of Yale-New Haven Hospital. The referral was made by the Connecticut State Police and the main  questions were: \"Is Dylan telling the truth, and did we think that she was sexually abused?\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://radaronline.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/yale-new-haven-hospital-allen.pdf|title=Child Sexual Abuse Clinic Evaluation of Dylan Farrow|date=1993-03-17|website=Radaronline.|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> Frank Maco, the Connecticut State's Attorney for the Litchfield district, declared in 1997 that he asked the Child Sexual Abuse Clinic of [[Yale\u2013New Haven Hospital]] to evaluate whether Dylan would make a viable witness.<ref name=ThibaultNov1997/><ref name=OrthOct2013/> The professionals of the Clinic met with the police and prosecutor Maco for preliminary information. {{cl-span|They collected more information from one of the detectives, John Mucherino, to be informed about all the data that the police had investigated |date=November 2019|reason-No idea what the hell this means. Suspect the last part of the sentence was left there by mistake after an edit. Something seems missing here}}. Between September 18 and November 13 they conducted a total of nine separate interviews with Dylan and her mother, Mia Farrow. On October 14 they interviewed Dylan's nanny Kristi Groteke, and between November 17 and January 7 they had three interviews with Woody Allen. Finally, they met with Mia Farrow to review the recording she had made of Dylan between August 5 and 6. Sophie Berge, the other nanny present on August 4, was also interviewed as well as the two psychotherapists treating the children, Dr. Coates and Dr. Stcuhtz.<ref name=\"Ewing2006p159\">{{cite book|title=Minds on Trial: Great Cases in Law and Psychology|last1=Ewing|first1=Charles Patrick|last2=McCann|first2=Joseph T.|date=2006|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|at=(pp.&nbsp;153\u2013164), p.&nbsp;159|chapter=Woody Allen and Mia Farrow: A Swing of King Solomon's Sword|ref=harv|author1-link=Charles Patrick Ewing}}</ref><ref name=Winter7Feb2014>{{cite news|last1=Winter|first1=Jessica|title=Woody Allen and Dylan Farrow: Just the Facts|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/life/culturebox/2014/02/woody_allen_and_dylan_farrow_digging_deeper_into_misleading_coverage.html|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Leventhal signed the team's report, while Dylan was interviewed by the social workers.<ref name=Winter7Feb2014/><ref name=OrthOct2013/> Completed in March 1993, the report concluded: \"It is our expert opinion that Dylan was not sexually abused by Mr. Allen.\"{{efn|[[Yale\u2013New Haven Hospital]] Child Sexual Abuse Clinic (1993): \"It is our expert opinion that Dylan was not sexually abused by Mr. Allen. Further, we believe that Dylan\u2019s statements on videotape and her statements to us during our evaluation do not refer to actual events that occurred to her on August 4th, 1992&nbsp;... In developing our opinion we considered three hypotheses to explain Dylan's statements. First, that Dylan\u2019s statements were true and that Mr. Allen had sexually abused her; second, that Dylan\u2019s statements were not true but were made up by an emotionally vulnerable child who was caught up in a disturbed family and who was responding to the stresses in the family; and third, that Dylan was coached or influenced by her mother, Ms. Farrow. While we can conclude that Dylan was not sexually abused, we can not be definite about whether the second formulation by itself or the third formulation by itself is true. We believe that it is more likely that a combination of these two formulations best explains Dylan\u2019s allegations of sexual abuse.\"<ref name=AllenFeb72014/><ref name=Ewing2006p159/><ref name=Winter7Feb2014/>}}\n\nThe team had proposed the study as an attempt to corroborate or falsify some of these basic hypotheses:\n# That the Dylan allegations were true and Allen had sexually abused her.\n# That the statements of Dylan were not true and had been made by an emotionally vulnerable minor trapped in a disturbed family situation and who responded to stress.\n# That she had been taught or influenced by her mother.\n\nThe Team members were the medical director of the Child Sexual Abuse Clinic since its foundation, Dr. John M. Leventhal,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slidex.tips/download/curriculum-vitae-john-m-leventhal-md|title=[PDF] CURRICULUM VITAE. John M. Leventhal, M.D. - Free Download PDF|website=slidex.tips|language=en|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> Dr. Julia Hamilton, who was also social worker and co-director of the Yale Medical Center Child Abuse Program,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/nhregister/obituary.aspx?n=julia-pearl-hamilton&pid=153301737|title=Julia Pearl Hamilton, Obituary.|website=|access-date=}}</ref> and Social Worker Ms. Sawyer, who had a masters in Social Work and ten years of experience. The social workers met Dylan in Yale New Haven every Friday for an hour or so. Kristi Groteke was interviewed for three hours.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=Mia & Woody : love and betrayal|first=Kristi|last=Groteke|date=1994|publisher=Carroll & Graf|isbn=|page=168|oclc=1036704501}}</ref> Maureen Orth stated that its conclusion was based, in part, on the view that Dylan had difficulty telling a consistent story and suffered from \"thought disturbances.\"<ref name=\"Orth7Feb2014\" /> According to the report, the important inconsistencies in Dylan's statement, the lack of spontaneity, and the impression of repeating something learned are the main reason for the conclusions.<ref name=\":2\" /> The report also stressed that Dylan felt that she had to solve her mother's problems,<ref name=\":4\" /> and indicated that the relationship between Mia Farrow and Dylan and Satchel was very disturbed and required immediate intensive psychotherapy.<ref name=\":3\" /> The team destroyed the original notes at the time of incorporating its content into the report.<ref name=\"Orth7Feb2014\" /><ref name=\"Ewing2006p159\" /> The report was immediately sent to the state police who had commissioned it, who informed Mia Farrow that same day and two days before Woody Allen was informed.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mia & Woody : love and betrayal|first=Kristi|last=Groteke|date=1994|publisher=Carroll & Graf|isbn=|pages=222|oclc=1036704501 }}</ref> Maco told a reporter in 1997 that Yale \"took the case and ran away with it.\"<ref name=\"ThibaultNov1997\" />\n\n===Custody trial===\n====Testimony====\nThe custody hearings began on March 19, 1993, in State Supreme Court in Manhattan,<ref name=Perez20March1993>{{cite news|last1=Perez-Pena|first1=Richard|title=Woody Allen Tells of Affair as Custody Battle Begins|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/03/20/nyregion/woody-allen-tells-of-affair-as-custody-battle-begins.html|work=The New York Times|date=March 20, 1993}}</ref> and ended on May 4.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Marks|first1=Peter|title=Allen-Farrow Trial Ends in New Round of Old Charges|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/05/nyregion/allen-farrow-trial-ends-in-new-round-of-old-charges.html|work=The New York Times|date=May 5, 1993}}</ref> Journalists were allowed in court but not with television cameras or microphones.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Penez-Pena|first1=Richard|title=Judge Bars Broadcasters From Farrow-Allen Case|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/12/12/nyregion/judge-bars-broadcasters-from-farrow-allen-case.html|work=The New York Times|date=December 12, 1992}}</ref> Taking the stand on the first day, Allen said the allegation was Farrow's vengeance for his affair with Soon Yi-Previn, which he had not intended to be \"anything but a private thing\"; he had hoped Farrow would not find out about it. He described her anger when she did.<ref name=Perez20March1993/>\n\n[[File:NYC - New York County Supreme Courthouse.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|New York State Supreme Courthouse]]\nKristie Groteke,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Groteke|first1=Kristie|last2=Rosen|first2=Marjorie|title=Mia & Woody: Love and Betrayal|url=https://archive.org/details/miawoodylovebetr00grot|url-access=registration|date=1994|publisher=Carroll & Graf Publishers|location=New York}}</ref> Farrow's babysitter, testified in April that for about 15\u201320 minutes on the afternoon in question, she had not been able to find Dylan or Allen in the house; she had assumed they were outside with the other children.<ref name=Stern10Feb2014/> Allen said he had gone to the bathroom during the disputed period.<ref name=MarksApril101993/> The children's French tutor, Sophie Berge, testified that she had noticed Dylan had been wearing no underwear under her dress that day.<ref name=Stern10Feb2014/><ref name=Winter7Feb2014/><ref name=Wypijewski26Feb2014>{{cite news|last1=Wypijewski|first1=Joann|title=Woody and Mia: A Modern Family Timeline|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/woody-and-mia-modern-family-timeline/|work=The Nation|date=February 26, 2014}}</ref> Another Farrow-household nanny, Monica Thompson, who was not present in the house on that day, told Allen's lawyers in two [[affidavit]]s in February 1993 that she had felt pressured by Farrow to support the allegation.<ref name=latimes020293/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Span|first1=Paula|title=Clash of the Nannies|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1993/04/07/clash-of-the-nannies/97418ba8-5206-4a36-888f-ce1d54b3f84f|work=The Washington Post|date=April 7, 1993}}</ref> Thompson said that Groteke had also had reservations; according to Thompson, Groteke told her, days after the allegation was made, that she \"did not have Dylan out of her sight for longer than five minutes. She did not remember Dylan being without her underwear.\"<ref name=latimes020293>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-02-02/news/mn-952_1_woody-allen|title=Nanny Casts Doubt on Farrow Charges|date=February 2, 1993|first=John J.|last=Goldman|work=Los Angeles Times|archivedate=January 19, 2018| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180119042801/http://articles.latimes.com/1993-02-02/news/mn-952_1_woody-allen|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Wypijewski26Feb2014/> Groteke acknowledged that she had had that conversation, although she only admitted to telling Thompson that she did not remember having lost sight of Dylan.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mia & Woody : love and betrayal|first=Kristi|last=Groteke|date=1994|publisher=Carroll & Graf|isbn=|pages=126|oclc=1036704501}}</ref> Ms. Thompson, who was Dylan's nanny since the girl was two months old, also stated that the charges against Woody Allen brought by Farrow were 'not true'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1993/01/26/Mias-nanny-says-Woody-was-the-better-parent/6587728024400/|title=Mia's nanny says Woody was the better parent|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref> Mavis Smith, the housekeeper of Mia Farrow for thirteen years, said she thought Woody Allen was a good father and in a telephone conversation said that in the thirteen years she had never seen Allen doing something sexual with Dylan or with Satchel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1993/04/06/Expert-witness-doubts-Woody-abused-adopted-daughter/2831734068800/|title=Expert witness doubts Woody abused adopted daughter|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2019-03-23 }}</ref>\n\nDr. Susan Coates, a Farrow family therapist, testified that Farrow had been so angry with Allen when she discovered the affair with Previn that Coates had feared for Allen's safety.<ref name=Marks30March1993>{{cite news|last1=Marks|first1=Peter|title=Doctor Recounts Threats By Farrow Against Allen|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/02/23/reviews/farrow-doctor.html|work=The New York Times|date=March 30, 1993}}</ref>  Farrow's lawyer accused Coates of gullibility for having accepted Allen's version of events.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Grimes|first1=William|title=Farrow's Lawyer Takes Aim at Doctor's Judgment|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/03/31/nyregion/farrow-s-lawyer-takes-aim-at-doctor-s-judgment.html|work=The New York Times|date=March 31, 1993}}</ref> Therapist Dr. Nancy Schultz was hired by Farrow and Allen in April 1991 because the child \"lived in her own fantasy world\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/04/02/nyregion/psychologist-testifies-about-visitation-rights-for-allen.html|title=Psychologist Testifies About Visitation Rights for Allen|last=Marks|first=Peter|date=1993-04-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-31|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Dr. Schultz testified that Dylan has become \"absorbed in what the fantasy is (and) that it became real\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Woody\u00b4s lawyer says Conn. cops siding with Mia|last=Hackett|first=Larry|date=1993-04-09|work=Daily News|access-date=}}</ref>Neither of them, Dr. Coates and Dr. Schultz, believed that sexual abuse had occurred.<ref name=\":0\" /> One of Allen's lawyers alleged that Farrow's lawyers had suggested \"the charges could be made to go away\" if Allen agreed to pay around $7 million. Alan Dershowitz, representing Farrow, said there had been an \"exploratory\" session to attempt mediation. \"To have this described as an extortionate meeting is ridiculous,\" he said. He added that Allen's lawyers were \"trying to set a trap, the trap failed and now they testify as if the trap succeeded\". One of Allen's lawyers acknowledged when cross-examined that the discussion about money related mostly to the children's education and medical care, as well as money owed for Farrow's film work for Allen.<ref name=MarksApril101993/> Levett, Mia Farrow's lawyer, acknowledged that he suggested various amounts to reach an agreement \"For child support, including household help: $17,000 a month until the youngest of the children turned 21, roughly $2.5 million factoring in inflation and interest. For tuition, assuming all three went to college: $800,000 to $900,000. Plus unspecified medical and, yes, psychiatric expenses. There might be a damage claim for Dylan, who had accused her father of molesting her. And some compensation for Mia Farrow, who'd earned $300,000 a year for her roles in Allen's annual films and was entitled to that sum for five to 10 years now that she was out of a job.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1993/04/16/dershowitz-woody-would-not-budge/0a95205b-6ca1-415f-8394-f212f705c954/|title=DERSHOWITZ: WOODY WOULD NOT BUDGE|last=Span|first=Paula|date=April 16, 1993|website=The Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref> \"Mr. Dershowitz echoed Mr. Levett's testimony. But he acknowledged that a proposal was made to intercede in the child-abuse investigation in favor of a private settlement. He added that the offer \"was not premised on any payments.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> In the program of Charlie Rose on October 14, 1992, Dershowitz stated about it: \"I don't think it ever had to come out. If he (Woody Allen) had not filed that suit, I don't think anybody would know the story today and I think it would be resolved quietly behind the scenes.\"<ref>{{Citation|title=Alan Dershowitz - Charlie Rose|url=https://charlierose.com/videos/18189|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\n'''John Leventhal''' of the Yale\u2013New Haven Child Sexual Abuse Clinic testified by [[Deposition (law)|deposition]] on 20 April. Citing inconsistencies in Dylan's account, he said that once it was discarded the hypothesis that Dylan's narrative corresponded to events that actually happened  the  Yale\u2013New Haven team \"had two hypotheses: one, that these were statements that were made by an emotionally disturbed child and then became fixed in her mind. And the other hypothesis was that she was coached or influenced by her mother. We did not come to a firm conclusion. We think that it was probably a combination.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Perez-Pena|first1=Richard|title=Doctor Cites Inconsistencies In Dylan Farrow's Statements|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/04/nyregion/doctor-cites-inconsistencies-in-dylan-farrow-s-statements.html|work=The New York Times|date=May 4, 1993}}</ref> Farrow and Allen both hired experts to discuss the report.<ref name=Ewing2006p159/> '''Anne Meltzer''', a forensic psychologist, testified for Allen that the report had \"reached conclusions that were supported well by the data they collected.\" She said the tape of Dylan making the allegation was \"flawed\" because it had been filmed by one side and not by a professional.<ref name=Ewing2006p159/><ref name=Marks28April1993/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Miller|first1=Tracey L.|title=Judge in Woody-Mia child custody case airs anti-Allen views|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1993/04/26/Judge-in-Woody-Mia-child-custody-case-airs-anti-Allen-views/5124735796800/|publisher=UPI|date=April 26, 1993}}</ref> '''Stephen Herman''', a child psychiatrist, testified for Farrow that the report was \"seriously flawed\", and that he could find no evidence of a thought disorder in Dylan's statements,<ref name=Ewing2006p159/><ref name=Marks28April1993>{{cite news|last1=Marks|first1=Peter|title=Yale Study About Allen Flawed, Expert Testifies|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/04/28/nyregion/yale-study-about-allen-flawed-expert-testifies.html|work=The New York Times|date=April 28, 1993}}</ref> however, Dr. Herman expressly stated that the report was not biased<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1993/04/28/evidence-with-a-double-edge/82fc8e5e-19c5-472a-981e-4adfdfa33b6d/|title=EVIDENCE WITH A DOUBLE EDGE|last=Span|first=Paula|date=1993-04-28|website=The Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Woody vs. Mia case drawing to a close|last=The Associated Press|date=1993-04-28|work=Asbury Park Press (Asbury Park, New Jersey)|access-date=}}</ref> and that he himself, in light of the evidence, could not reach any conclusion regarding the allegation of abuse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1993/04/28/evidence-with-a-double-edge/82fc8e5e-19c5-472a-981e-4adfdfa33b6d/|title=EVIDENCE WITH A DOUBLE EDGE|last=Span|first=Paula|date=1993-04-28|website=The Washington Post.|access-date=}}</ref> That it could have happened, or it could not have happened.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1993/04/27/Woody-Mia-judge-questions-value-of-expert-testimony/6160735883200/|title=Woody-Mia judge questions value of expert testimony|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2019-03-21 }}</ref> That the evidence was inconclusive.<ref name=\"Shea7Feb2014\" /> To [[Charles Patrick Ewing]] and Joseph McCann, the most damaging criticism of the report was that the team had destroyed its notes from the interviews it conducted, which meant the court could not test the validity of the report's conclusions; they write that forensic experts have an obligation to retain their notes for review. Another criticism was that the team was unwilling to testify in court, except via Leventhal's deposition.{{sfnp|Ewing|McCann|2006|p=160}} Dr. Herman also recognized the tape of Dylan making the allegation was flawed because it was made in a way that \"set a tone for a child about how to answer\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mia & Woody : love and betrayal|first=Kristi|last=Groteke|date=1994|publisher=Carroll & Graf|isbn=|pages=169|oclc=1036704501 }}</ref> He also concluded that there was no point in passing another forensic evaluation to Dylan on the allegation.<ref name=\"Shea7Feb2014\" />\n\nAll the psychiatric experts who declared in the trial agreed that Allen was able to fulfill a positive role in Dylan's therapy.<ref name=\"appeal1994\" /><ref name=\"Shea7Feb2014\" />\n\n====Decision====\nIn his 33-page decision in June 1993,<ref name=Shea7Feb2014/> Justice Elliott Wilk rejected Allen's bid for custody of the three children and rejected the allegation of sexual abuse, denied Allen immediate visitation rights with Dylan, saying of Allen's behavior toward Dylan that it was \"grossly inappropriate and that measures must be taken to protect her\" while pointing out that Allen's inappropriate behavior was not sexual in nature.<ref name=Shea7Feb2014/><ref name=Marks8June1993/>{{sfnp|Ewing|McCann|2006|p=161}} His criticism of Allen's parenting was harsh.{{sfnp|Ewing|McCann|2006|pp=160\u2013161}}<ref name=Stern10Feb2014/> Rejecting Allen's portrayal of Farrow as a \"woman scorned\", Wilk said there was no credible evidence that she had coached Dylan  although the videotape she made of Dylan compromised the investigation of sexual abuse, and he criticized Allen for his \"trial strategy\" of turning family members and employees against one another. The Yale\u2013New Haven team's unwillingness to testify in court, except through Leventhal's deposition, together with the destruction of its notes, had rendered its report, he wrote, \"sanitized and, therefore, less credible\".{{sfnp|Ewing|McCann|2006|p=160}}<ref name=Stern10Feb2014/><ref name=Shea7Feb2014>{{cite news|last1=Shea|first1=Danny|title=Here's The 1993 Woody Allen Custody Ruling In Its Damning, Detailed Entirety|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/danny-shea/heres-the-1993-woody-alle_b_4746866.html|work=HuffPost|date=February 7, 2014}}; {{cite court | litigants = Allen v. Farrow (1993) | court = N.Y. Sup. | date = June 7, 1993 }}</ref><ref name=Marks8June1993>{{cite news|last1=Marks|first1=Peter|title=Allen Loses to Farrow in Bitter Custody Battle|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/02/23/reviews/farrow-verdict.html|work=The New York Times|date=June 8, 1993}}</ref> Wilk called the case \"frivolous\" and ordered Allen to pay Farrow's costs,<ref name=Marks8June1993/>{{sfnp|Ewing|McCann|2006|p=161}} Regarding the allegation of abuse, Wilk concluded that the evidence did not support that it had occurred, although he was not sure that the evidence demonstrated conclusively that it had not happened. The judge did not order a new battery of forensic evidence with Dylan because all the experts agree with the conclusion expressed by the expert appointed by Farrow that it would not be beneficial or provide useful information. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Criminal inquiry, social services===\nThe police interviewed Allen in Litchfield in January 1993 for over three hours. He said he had never been in the attic crawl space; when the police said they had taken fingerprints in there, he said it was possible that his prints were there. The forensic specialist chief of Connecticut\u2019s state crime laboratory,  Dr.Henry Lee, said that what police has found in the crawl space was hair fibers   and that the evidence could not place Allen in the attic.  On September 20 that year, Frank Maco, the State's Attorney, accompanied by a female police detective, talked to Dylan; Maco told a reporter in 1997: \"I saw complete withdrawal any time I tried to discuss the incident.\"<ref name=ThibaultNov1997/><ref name=OrthOct2013/>\n\nOn September 24, 1993, Maco held a news conference to say that he would not pursue the molestation allegation, despite having [[probable cause]], citing a desire not to traumatize Dylan.<ref name=ThibaultNov1997>{{cite news|last1=Thibault|first1=Andy|title=People: Frank Maco|url=http://www.connecticutmag.com/the-connecticut-story/mia-farrow-s-vanity-fair-interview-references-connecticut-magazine-article/article_4327cac7-ffef-5eb5-9c19-fdaf70e84855.html|work=Connecticut Magazine|date=November 1997}}</ref><ref name=Henneberger25Sept1993>{{cite news |first=Melinda|last=Henneberger|url = https://www.nytimes.com/1993/09/25/nyregion/connecticut-prosecutor-won-t-file-charges-against-woody-allen.html | title = Connecticut Prosecutor Won't File Charges Against Woody Allen | work = The New York Times | date = September 25, 1993}}</ref><ref name=CBS18Jan2018>{{cite news|title=Dylan Farrow details her sexual molestation allegations against Woody Allen|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/dylan-farrow-interview-today-gayle-king-full-transcript-woody-allen-me-too/|publisher=CBS News|date=January 18, 2018}}</ref> In the official Statement of decision of the prosecution, Frank Maco acknowledged that even in the case of custody and with a more favorable standard of proof for the accusation that \"proof beyond a reasonable doubt\" it had been impossible to reach the conclusion that the abuse had occurred. He also acknowledged that the nature of the evidence was a fertile ground for the defense and \u201cwould not have the same probative  as it did in the New York Supreme Court custody case\u201d; so he considered  his duty \u201cto avoid the unjustifiable risk of exposing a child to the rigors and uncertainties of a questionable prosecution\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/204662575/Statement-of-Decision-9-24-1993|title=Statement of Decision 9-24-1993|website=Scribd|language=en|access-date=2019-05-04}}</ref>\n\nIn a letter to the New York Department of Social Services, Allen's psychotherapist Kathryn Prescott stated that Allen's psychological profile \"was definitely not that of a sexual offender\" and also stated \u201cThere has never been any suggestion that Mr. Allen was suffering from a sexual perversion / deviant sexual behavior.\"<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1241&dat=19930421&id=Y35TAAAAIBAJ&sjid=FIYDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6340,6035301&hl=en \"Therapist says Woody Allen No Sex Offender\"]. Jeanne King, ''[[Daily News (Kingsport)|Daily News]]'', (p.12) April 21st, 1993. Retrieved 14 October 2018.</ref> The New York Department of Social Services closed its own 14-month investigation in October 1993; its letter to Allen stated: \"No credible evidence was found that the child named in this report has been abused or maltreated. This report has, therefore, been considered unfounded.\"<ref name=\"PerezPena26Oct1993\">{{cite news|last1=P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a|first1=Richard|title=Agency Drops Abuse Inquiry in Allen Case|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/26/nyregion/agency-drops-abuse-inquiry-in-allen-case.html|work=The New York Times|date=October 26, 1993}}</ref>\n\nAllen filed complaints with the Connecticut Criminal Justice Commission and the statewide bar counsel over Maco's statement about probable cause.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Perez-Pena|first1=Richard|title=Woody Allen Asks Connecticut to Discipline Prosecutor|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/14/nyregion/woody-allen-asks-connecticut-to-discipline-prosecutor.html|work=The New York Times|date=October 14, 1993}}</ref> The former dismissed the complaint in November 1993.<ref name=Kennedy4Nov1993>{{cite news|last1=Kennedy|first1=Randy|title=Woody Allen Fails to Beat A Prosecutor|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/11/04/nyregion/woody-allen-fails-to-beat-a-prosecutor.html|work=The New York Times|date=November 4, 1993}}</ref> In February 1994 the statewide Grievance Committee ruled that, while Maco had not violated the state's code of conduct for lawyers, his statement was a cause of \"grave concern.\" In addition, Maco had sent a copy of his statement to the judge who was deciding whether to overturn Allen's adoption of Dylan and Moses. That act was \"inappropriate, unsolicited and potentially prejudicial,\" the panel ruled.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Perez-Pena|first1=Richard|title=Panel Criticizes Prosecutor In Inquiry on Woody Allen|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/02/24/nyregion/panel-criticizes-prosecutor-in-inquiry-on-woody-allen.html|work=The New York Times|date=February 24, 1994}}</ref>\n\n===Allen's appeals, other legal action===\nIn December 1992 Farrow began legal action, which was ultimately unsuccessful, to have Allen's adoption of Dylan and Moses declared void. Her position was based, in part, on her view that Allen's affair with Soon-Yi Previn had begun before the adoption was finalized on December 17, 1991.<ref name=Perez19June1993>{{cite news|last1=Perez-Pena|first1=Richard|title=Farrow Spurns Allen's Plea For a Truce|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/06/10/nyregion/farrow-spurns-allen-s-plea-for-a-truce.html|work=The New York Times|date=June 19, 1993}}</ref><ref name=Stern10Feb2014/> Allen stated that the sexual relationship had started in the last week of 1991.<ref name=Perez19June1993/> Allen offered not to appeal the custody ruling if Farrow would drop her attempt to have his adoption of Dylan and Moses declared void, but she refused.<ref name=Perez19June1993/>\n\nIn January 1994 Allen appealed Wilk's decision.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Perez Pena|first1=Richard|title=Woody Allen Appeals Judgment in Custody Case|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/01/14/nyregion/woody-allen-appeals-judgment-in-custody-case.html|work=The New York Times|date=January 14, 1994}}</ref> Of the molestation allegation, the appellate court  concluded \"the evidence in support of the allegations remains inconclusive,\" stated that its \"review of the record militates against a finding that Ms. Farrow fabricated the allegations without any basis\" and explicitly corrected Justice Wilk by stating that the Yale\u2013New Haven team's view that Dylan had a tendency to \"withdraw into a fantasy,\" and that she had offered inconsistent accounts, had to be taken into account. As elements suggesting that the abuse could have occurred but not being sufficient for this conclusion to be more likely than the contrary the court list \"the testimony given at trial by the individuals caring for the children that day, the videotape of Dylan made by Ms. Farrow the following day and the accounts of Dylan's behavior toward Mr. Allen both before and after the alleged instance of abuse.\" The court was critical of Allen's parenting skills and relationship with Soon-Yi Previn. The appeal failed, although two of the five judges said the visitation rights regarding Satchel were too restrictive.<ref name=appeal1994>[https://www.leagle.com/decision/1994524197ad2d3271461 Allen v. Farrow (1994)] (Appellate Division of the Supreme Court of the State of New York, First Department, May 12, 1994).</ref> Allen appealed again, and in July 1995 the [[New York Court of Appeals]] upheld the original decision.<ref name=appeal1995>[https://www.leagle.com/decision/1995352215ad2d1371310 Allen v. Farrow (1995)] (Appellate Division of the Supreme Court of the State of New York, First Department, May 4, 1995).{{pb}}\n{{cite news|last1=Brozan|first1=Nadine|title=Chronicle|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/07/06/style/chronicle-460695.html|work=The New York Times|date=July 6, 1995}}</ref>\n\n==Later statements, reception==\n===''What Falls Away''===\nIn Mia Farrow's 1997 memoir, ''What Falls Away'', Farrow repeated the accusation that Allen had sexually abused Dylan Farrow.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Farrow|first1=Mia|title=What Falls Away|date=1997|publisher=Bantam|location=New York|page=271|ref=harv}}</ref> Farrow's abuse allegation was mentioned in several of the book's reviews.<ref>\" Ms. Farrow claimed that Mr. Allen had long been focusing inappropriate sexual attention on their 7-year-old adoptive daughter Dylan.\"[https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/books/98/02/01/bsp/25818.html]\"Intimate Strangers\". [[Kathryn Harrison]], ''[[The New York Times]]'' 23rd February, 1997. Retrieved 14th October, 2018.</ref><ref>\"In Farrow's life, apparently, no gruesome situation goes untopped: She further claims that Allen was guilty of sexually abusing her 7-year-old adopted daughter.\" [http://articles.latimes.com/1997-03-02/books/bk-33844_1_mia-farrow \"Rosemary's Mother\".] Celia McGee, ''[[LA Times]], March 2nd, 1997. Retrieved October 14th, 2018.</ref>\n\n===Siblings, open letter===\n[[File:Ronan Farrow, Ukraine, 23 March 2012 (cropped) .jpg|thumb|left|[[Ronan Farrow]], 2012]]\nWhen Allen won the [[Golden Globe Cecil B. DeMille Award]] in January 2014, Mia Farrow and Satchel (now going under the name [[Ronan Farrow]] and working as a journalist) tweeted objections.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pulver|first1=Andrew|title=Woody Allen Golden Globe greeted with derision by Mia and Ronan Farrow|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jan/13/golden-globes-woody-allen-mia-farrow-tweet|work=The Guardian|date=January 13, 2014}}</ref> Dylan Farrow, by then 28, repeated the molestation allegation the following month in an open letter in ''The New York Times'' blog of [[Nicholas Kristof]], a family friend. Writing that Allen had made her feel uncomfortable \"for as long as [she] could remember\", she alleged, for example, that he would get into bed with her in his underwear and that she would hide to avoid him.<ref name=Farrow1Feb2014>{{cite news|first=Dylan|last=Farrow|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/02/opinion/sunday/kristof-dylan-farrows-story.html |title=Dylan Farrow's Story |work=The New York Times |date=February 1, 2014}}</ref> Allen called the allegations \"untrue and disgraceful\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Woody Allen Calls Sexual Abuse Claims 'Untrue and Disgraceful'|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/woody-allen-calls-sexual-abuse-claims-untrue-and-disgraceful-1201083173/|work=Variety|date=February 2, 2014}}</ref> and responded with an op-ed in ''The New York Times''.<ref name=AllenFeb72014>{{cite news|last1=Allen|first1=Woody|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/09/opinion/sunday/woody-allen-speaks-out.html|title=Woody Allen Speaks Out|work=The New York Times|date=February 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Thibault|first1=Andy|title=Cool Justice: New York Times bent rules for Woody Allen, but not for Frank Maco|url=http://www.nhregister.com/columns/article/Cool-Justice-New-York-Times-bent-rules-for-Woody-11384930.php|work=New Haven Register|date=February 14, 2014}}</ref> The newspaper allowed Dylan's open letter 936 words within Kristof's blog, Ronan wrote, while Allen's op-ed was given twice the length and published in the print edition.<ref name=Farrow11May2016/>\n\nRonan, aged four in 1992, has been critical of Allen for several years; in 2011 he tweeted: \"He's my father married to my sister. That makes me his son and his brother-in-law. That is such a moral transgression.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ullman|first1=Joan|title=Ronan Farrow: Man on a Mission|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/uncharted-customs/201801/ronan-farrow-man-mission|work=Psychology Today|date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> In ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' in May 2016, he wrote that, following the publication of Dylan's open letter, his colleagues had forwarded him the daily emails \"blasted out by Allen's powerful publicist\", with an open [[Carbon copy|cc list]], offering talking points for reporters and the names of friends, therapists and lawyers willing to be interviewed. He wrote: \"Reporters on the receiving end of this kind of PR blitz have to wonder if deviating from the talking points might jeopardize their access to all the other A-list clients.\"<ref name=Farrow11May2016>{{Cite news|first=Ronan|last=Farrow|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/my-father-woody-allen-danger-892572|title=My Father, Woody Allen, and the Danger of Questions Unasked (Guest Column)|newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date= May 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDylan's brother Moses Farrow, who was 14 in 1992, has taken a different view; he has reconciled with Allen and is now estranged from the Farrow family. When Dylan published her open letter, he said in an interview that several people had been in the house on the disputed day and that \"no one, not my father or sister, was off in any private spaces\". He asserted that Mia Farrow had cultivated a climate in which he and his siblings had felt compelled to support her views, and that she had both physically and emotionally abused him.<ref>{{cite news|first=Michael|last=Rothman|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/dylan-farrows-brother-moses-mia-farrow-woody-allen/story?id=22377303|title=Dylan Farrow's Brother Moses Says Mia Farrow, Not Woody Allen Was Abusive |publisher= ABC News |date= February 5, 2014}}{{pb}}\n{{cite news|first=Andrew|last=Pulver|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/feb/05/woody-allen-dylan-farrow-moses|title=Moses Farrow defends Woody Allen over child abuse allegations |date=5 February 2013|work= The Guardian}}</ref> He repeated the allegations in 2017 to [[Eric Lax]], one of Allen's biographers.<ref>{{cite book|first=Eric|last=Lax|author-link=Eric Lax|url=|title=Start To Finish: Woody Allen and the Art of MovieMaking |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf |location=New York|date=2017|pp=123\u2013129}}</ref> Moses Farrow offered additional details defending Allen in a May 23, 2018 blog post.<ref name=MosesFarrowMay2018>{{cite web|url=https://mosesfarrow.blogspot.nl/2018/05/a-son-speaks-out-by-moses-farrow.html|title=A Son Speaks Out |first=Moses |last=Farrow |publisher=Moses Farrow official blog|date=May 23, 2018|accessdate=May 26, 2018|archivedate=May 26, 2018|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180526025527/http://mosesfarrow.blogspot.com/2018/05/a-son-speaks-out-by-moses-farrow.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In that letter he accused [[Mia Farrow]] of child abuse and neglect, coupled with a [[white savior]] complex: \"When Soon-Yi was young, Mia once threw a large porcelain centerpiece at her head. Luckily it missed, but the shattered pieces hit her legs. Years later, Mia beat her with a telephone receiver.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/moses-farrow-defends-woody-allen-claims-mia-farrow-was-abusive-1114452|title=Woody Allen's Son Moses Farrow Defends Father, Claims Mother Mia Farrow Was Abusive|work= The Hollywood Reporter | first=Evan|last= Real|date=May 23, 2018|accessdate=June 9, 2018|archivedate=June 1, 2018| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180601193441/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/moses-farrow-defends-woody-allen-claims-mia-farrow-was-abusive-1114452|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=MosesFarrowMay2018 /> However, the most important part of Moses' testimony is related to Dylan's allegation of sexual abuse. Moses explains that on the afternoon of August 4 he was at home: \"As the \u201cman of the house\u201d that day, I had promised to keep an eye out for any trouble, and I was doing just that. I remember where Woody sat in the TV room, and I can picture where Dylan and Satchel were. Not that everybody stayed glued to the same spot, but I deliberately made sure to note everyone's coming and going. I do remember that Woody would leave the room on occasion, but never with Dylan. He would wander into another room to make a phone call, read the paper, use the bathroom, or step outside to get some air and walk around the large pond on the property.\"<ref name=\"MosesFarrowMay2018\" /> Moses also indicates that the memory that his sister keeps from having suffered abuse while focusing her attention on an electric train set is not possible: \"It\u2019s a precise and compelling narrative, but there\u2019s a major problem: there ''was'' no electric train set in that attic. There was, in fact, no way for kids to play up there, even if we had wanted to. It was an unfinished crawl space, under a steeply-angled gabled roof, with exposed nails and floorboards, billows of fiberglass insulation, filled with mousetraps and droppings and stinking of mothballs, and crammed with trunks full of hand-me-down clothes and my mother\u2019s old wardrobes. The idea that the space could possibly have accommodated a functioning electric train set, circling around the attic, is ridiculous.\"<ref name=\"MosesFarrowMay2018\" />\n\n===Op-ed and interview===\n{{see also|Weinstein effect|Me Too (hashtag)|Time's Up (movement)}}\n{{external media\n| float  = right\n| width  = 240px\n| image1 = [https://cbsnews3.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2018/01/16/b309fed0-671f-43e1-9d6a-1e8da4bb86a0/thumbnail/1200x630/1ccd4065fabab5f850a3528aedf7d545/ctm-dylan-farrow-gayle-king.jpg Dylan Farrow] ''(left)'' speaks to [[Gayle King]], ''CBS This Morning'', January 18, 2018.\n}}\nIn December 2017, following the Weinstein controversy, Dylan Farrow wrote an op-ed in the ''Los Angeles Times'' asking, \"Why has the #MeToo revolution spared Woody Allen?\"<ref name=Farrow7Dec2017>{{cite news|first=Dylan|last=Farrow |url=http://www.latimes.com/opinion/op-ed/la-oe-farrow-woody-allen-me-too-20171207-story.html |title=Dylan Farrow: Why has the #MeToo revolution spared Woody Allen? |work=The Los Angeles Times|date=December 7, 2017}}</ref> She repeated the molestation allegation in January 2018 in a television interview with [[Gayle King]] for ''[[CBS This Morning]]''.<ref name=CBS18Jan2018/> Allen issued a statement in response:\n\n{{quote|[E]ven though the Farrow family is cynically using the opportunity afforded by the Time's Up movement to repeat this discredited allegation, that doesn't make it any more true today than it was in the past. I never molested my daughter \u2013 as all investigations concluded a quarter of a century ago.<ref name=CBS2018re />}}\n\n[[File:Woody Allen statue, Oviedo, Spain, November 2014.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|left|Statue in [[Oviedo]]]]\nAfter Dylan Farrow's 2014 open letter, several actors issued statements critical of Allen, including [[Rosie O'Donnell]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Rosie O'Donnell says she believes Dylan Farrow's allegations|url=https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/TV/2014/02/07/Rosie-ODonnell-says-she-believes-Dylan-Farrows-allegations/UPI-73171391796252/|publisher=UPI|date=February 2, 2014}}</ref> [[Lena Dunham]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nianias|first1=Helen|title=Lena Dunham rips into Woody Allen and calls him a 'perv' at Sundance|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/lena-dunham-rips-into-woody-allen-and-calls-him-a-perv-at-sundance-10002087.html|work=The Independent|date=January 26, 2015}}</ref> [[Sarah Silverman]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Miller|first1=Julie|title=Is It Wrong to Work with Woody Allen?|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/07/woody-allen-kate-winslet-justin-timberlake-movie|work=Vanity Fair|date=July 7, 2016}}</ref> and [[Susan Sarandon]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lang|first1=Brent|title=Susan Sarandon on Woody Allen: 'He Sexually Assaulted a Child'|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/markets-festivals/susan-sarandon-woody-allen-rape-1201775122/|work=Variety|date=May 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe mood changed further as a result of the #MeToo and Time's Up movements and Dylan's op-ed. In November 2017 during a [[International Day for the Elimination of Violence against Women|women's rally]], a banner referring to the allegation was hung around the neck of Allen's statue in [[Oviedo]], Spain, and a women's group later asked that the statue be removed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2018/01/22/an-abuser-and-pervert-women-in-spain-want-a-statue-of-woody-allen-removed/|title='An abuser and pervert': Women in Spain want a statue of Woody Allen removed|work=The Washington Post|first=Amanda|last=Erickson|date=January 22, 2018}}{{pb}}{{cite news|url=https://www.thelocal.es/20180122/women-demand-woody-allen-statue-removed-in-oviedo-after-sex-molestation-allegations|title=Women demand Woody Allen statue removed in Oviedo after sex molestation allegations|work=The Local Spain|first=Fiona|last=Govan|date=January 22, 2018}}{{pb}}\n{{cite news|title=A man looks at a banner on sculpture of Woody Allen during the rally on the World Day for the Elimination of Violence against Women in Oviedo|url=http://news.trust.org/item/20171125172209-q3evk|agency=Reuters|date=November 25, 2017}}</ref> From October 2017 statements supportive of Dylan, or expressing regret at having worked with Allen, were issued by [[Griffin Newman]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2017/10/tick-actor-griffin-newman-regrets-working-with-woody-allen.html|title=The Tick Actor Griffin Newman Regrets Working With Woody Allen, Promises to Donate His Salary From the Film|website=Vulture.com|first=Jackson|last=McHenry|date=October 16, 2017}}</ref> [[Ellen Page]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/11/ellen-page-brett-ratner-facebook-post|work=Vanity Fair|title= Ellen Page Accuses Brett Ratner of 'Homophobic and Abusive Behavior'|first=Yohan|last=Desata|date=November 10, 2017| accessdate=June 9, 2018| archivedate=January 29, 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.is/KwFLK|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=EllenPageFacebook>{{cite web| url=https://www.facebook.com/EllenPage/posts/10155212835577449| first=Ellen|last=Page|authorlink=Ellen Page|title='You should fuck her to make her realize she's gay'|publisher= Ellen Page verified [[Facebook]]|date=November 10, 2017| accessdate=June 9, 2018| archivedate= January 29, 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.is/WdRhV|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Evan Rachel Wood]],<ref>{{cite tweet|user= evanrachelwood|number=805397149282422784|title=That was years before I read Dylan's letter|first=Evan |last=Rachel Wood|date=December 4, 2016|authorlink=Evan Rachel Wood|accessdate=January 18, 2018|archivedate=June 9, 2018| archiveurl=https://archive.is/tJcEH|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brit.co/evan-rachel-wood-just-took-a-stance-against-this-hollywood-heavyweight-following-maria-schneiders-sexual-assault-revelation/|title= Evan Rachel Wood Just Took a Stand Against This Hollywood Heavyweight|publisher=[[Brit + Co]]|first=Nicole |last= Briese|date =December 5, 2016 |accessdate=June 9, 2018|archivedate=June 9, 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.is/GGlE0|url-status=live}}</ref> [[David Krumholtz]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Verhoeven |first=Beatrice |title='Wonder Wheel' Actor Calls Working With Woody Allen 'One of My Most Heartbreaking Mistakes'|work=TheWrap |date=January 6, 2018|url-status=live |url=https://www.thewrap.com/wonder-wheel-david-krumholtz-regrets-working-with-woody-allen/}}</ref> [[Greta Gerwig]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bruni|first1=Frank|last2=Gerwig|first2=Greta|last3=Sorkin|first3=Aaron|title=Greta Gerwig, Aaron Sorkin: Hollywood Must Change|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/09/opinion/greta-gerwig-woody-allen-aaron-sorkin.html|work=The New York Times|date=January 9, 2018}}</ref> [[Mira Sorvino]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Sorvino |first=Mira |url= https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/mira-sorvino-letter-dylan-farrow_us_5a56b660e4b08a1f624b47e0|title=Exclusive: Mira Sorvino's Open Letter To Dylan Farrow |work=HuffPost |date=January 11, 2018}}</ref> [[Rebecca Hall]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Levin|first1=Sam|title=Rebecca Hall says she won't work with Woody Allen again|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jan/12/rebecca-hall-woody-allen-dylan-farrow|work=The Guardian|date=12 January 2018}}</ref> [[Timoth\u00e9e Chalamet]],<ref name=Harmon16Jan2018>{{cite news|last1=Harmon|first1=Steph|title=Timoth\u00e9e Chalamet: 'I don't want to profit from my work on Woody Allen's film'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jan/16/timothee-chalamet-i-dont-want-to-profit-from-my-work-on-woody-allens-film|work=The Guardian|date=16 January 2018}}</ref> [[Rachel Brosnahan]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/rachel-brosnahan-says-she-regrets-working-woody-allen-1075123|title=Rachel Brosnahan Says She Regrets Working With Woody Allen|work=The Hollywood Reporter|first=Scott|last=Feinberg|date=January 17, 2018}}</ref> [[Natalie Portman]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/5106106/woody-allen-dylan-farrow-actors/|title=These Actors All Worked With Woody Allen. Now They Regret It and Support Dylan Farrow|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|first=Samantha|last=Cooney|date=January 18, 2018}}</ref> [[Colin Firth]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jan/18/colin-firth-woody-allen-accusations-film|title=Colin Firth says he will not work with Woody Allen again|website=The Guardian|first=Sam|last=Levin|date=January 18, 2018}}{{pb}}\n{{cite news|last1=Leszkiewicz|first1=Anna|title=Sadly, Colin Firth's words on Woody Allen have a power that women's don't|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/culture/film/2018/01/sadly-colin-firth-s-words-woody-allen-have-power-women-s-don-t|work=New Statesman|date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> [[Hayley Atwell]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jan/28/hayley-atwell-interview-dry-powder|title=Hayley Atwell: 'It's very liberating to play someone who's unapologetically ruthless'|website=The Guardian|first=Michael|last=Hogan|date=January 28, 2018}}</ref> [[Freida Pinto]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/jan/27/freida-pinto-i-wouldnt-work-with-woody-allen-again|title=Freida Pinto: 'I wouldn't work with Woody Allen again'|website=[[The Guardian]]|first=Simon|last=Hattenstone|date=January 27, 2019|accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref> and [[John Turturro]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/john-turturro-interview-gloria-bell-woody-allen-going-place-the-big-lebowski-a8946846.html|title=John Turturro interview: 'I wouldn't cast Woody Allen now'|website=[[The Independent]]|date=June 7, 2019|accessdate=June 8, 2019}}</ref> Newman, Hall, Chalamet and Fanning said they would donate their earnings from Allen's film ''[[A Rainy Day in New York]]'' (2018) to charities.<ref name=\"Harmon16Jan2018\" />\n\nIn January 2018, the [[Goodspeed Opera House]] in Connecticut canceled its adaptation of Allen's film ''[[Bullets over Broadway]]'' (1994).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/25/theater/woody-allen-bullets-over-broadway.html|title=Goodspeed Cancels Woody Allen Musical|last1=Paulson|first1=Michael|date=June 25, 2018|work=The New York Times}}</ref> In February 2018, Circle Theater in [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]] also canceled their adaptation of ''Bullets over Broadway''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/grand-rapids/index.ssf/2018/02/grand_rapids_theater_latest_to.html|title=Grand Rapids theater cancels Woody Allen's musical in support of #MeToo|last=Martinez|first=Shandra|date=February 1, 2018|publisher=MLive.com|accessdate= February 1, 2018|archivedate=June 9, 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.is/Ihhp4| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Elle Fanning]] stated that she regretted her decision \"if it hurt anyone\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2018/03/11/elle-fanning-regrets-working-woody-allen-upset-7378123/|title=Elle Fanning only regrets working with Woody Allen if you've been upset by it|date=2018-03-11|website=Metro|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref> Joaquin Phoenix stated, \"When I worked with Woody, I knew about the stuff that had come up years ago, I know his daughter ended up writing an open letter. I was not aware of that when we worked together.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2018/01/22/joaquin-phoenix-working-woody-allen-knew-stuff-had-come-up-years-ago/1052501001/|title=Joaquin Phoenix 'not aware' of Dylan Farrow's open letter when he worked with Woody Allen|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref> When asked if he'd work with Allen, [[Peter Sarsgaard]] said \"it's such a complicated question. I've already done a Woody Allen movie\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/movies/peter-sarsgaard-wont-work-woody-allen-again-jeff-daniels-remains-undecided/|title=Peter Sarsgaard Says He Won't Work with Woody Allen Again, But Jeff Daniels Remains Undecided|website=PEOPLE.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref> [[Chloe Sevigny]] stated \u201cI have my own turmoil that I\u2019m grappling with over that decision, would I work with him again? Probably not.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/chloe-sevigny-woody-allen-melinda-and-melinda-1202670722/|title=Chloe Sevigny Says She Would 'Probably Not' Work With Woody Allen Again (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Setoodeh|first=Ramin|last2=Setoodeh|first2=Ramin|date=2018-01-20|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref> [[Marion Cotillard]] when asked replied, \"I have to say today, yeah, if he were to ask me again \u2026 I don\u2019t think it would ever happen because the experience we had together was very odd. I admire some of his work but we had no connection on set.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jan/19/marion-cotillard-woody-allen-experience-midnight-in-paris|title=Marion Cotillard on Woody Allen: 'The experience we had together was very odd'|last=staff|first=Guardian|date=2018-01-19|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-07-24|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nThose expressing support for Allen included [[Barbara Walters]] and [[Diane Keaton]] in 2014,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rayman|first1=Noah|title=Barbara Walters Defends Woody Allen|url=http://time.com/3883/barbara-walters-defends-woody-allen-amid-abuse-claims/|work=Variety|date=February 4, 2014}}{{pb}}{{cite news|last1=Brockes|first1=Emma|title=Diane Keaton: 'I love Woody. And I believe my friend'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/may/03/diane-keaton-i-love-woody-allen-i-believe-my-friend|work=The Guardian|date=May 3, 2014}}</ref> as well as [[Javier Bardem]], [[Jude Law]], [[Alec Baldwin]], [[Bill Maher]], and Keaton again in January 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/04/javier-bardem-woody-allen|title=Javier Bardem Is on Woody Allen's Side: \"I Am Very Shocked by This Sudden Treatment\"|last=Nast|first=Cond\u00e9|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/nov/20/jude-law-shelving-woody-allen-amazon-studios-shame-rainy-day-new-york|title='A terrible shame': Jude Law defends Woody Allen film after Amazon shelves it|last=Pulver|first=Andrew|date=2018-11-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-07-24|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Chuba|first1=Kirsten|title=Alec Baldwin Criticizes Stars Denouncing Woody Allen: 'It's Unfair and Sad'|url=https://variety.com/2018/biz/news/alec-baldwin-stars-denouncing-woody-allen-unfair-and-sad-1202665291/|work=Variety|date=January 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/diane-keaton-defends-woody-allen-sexual-abuse-1202680654/|title=Diane Keaton Defends Woody Allen: 'I Continue to Believe Him'|last=Fernandez|first=Matt|date=2018-01-29|work=Variety|access-date=2018-05-03|language=en-US}}</ref> [[Robert B. Weide]], who made a documentary film on Allen,<ref>{{Citation|last=Weide|first=Robert B.|title=Woody Allen: A Documentary|date=2011-11-20|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1895299/|others=Woody Allen, Letty Aronson, Marshall Brickman|accessdate=2018-03-08}}</ref> published his rebuttals to the Farrow allegations in an article ''The Woody Allen Allegations: Not So Fast''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/01/27/the-woody-allen-allegations-not-so-fast|title=The Woody Allen Allegations: Not So Fast|last=Weide|first=Robert B.|date=2014-01-27|work=The Daily Beast|access-date=2018-03-08|language=en}}</ref> [[Cherry Jones]], addressing the topic, said, \"There are those who are comfortable in their certainty. I am not. I don't know the truth ... When we condemn by instinct our democracy is on a slippery slope.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ryzik|first1=Melena|last2=Barnes|first2=Brooks|title=Can Woody Allen Work in Hollywood Again?|url= https://nyti.ms/2Fovqcm |work=The New York Times|date=January 28, 2018}}</ref> [[Emily Mortimer]], when asked about Allen in an interview, said  \"I believe in [[due process]]...I think these things really need to go through all the legal processes before anyone can judge. I don\u2019t really have an answer to those questions.\"<ref>Macnab, Geoffrey. (February 19, 2018) [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/emily-mortimer-interview-the-bookshop-woody-allen-mary-poppins-returns-jane-banks-disney-john-a8217661.html \"Emily Mortimer Interview\"]. ''[[The Independent]]''. Retrieved March 16, 2018.</ref> [[Jeff Daniels]], when asked if he would work with Allen again, responded: \"I believe Dylan Farrow. Would I do another one with Woody? The difficult decision would be to turn him down, because of ''[[The Purple Rose of Cairo]]''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2018/02/jeff-daniels-woody-allen-difficult-decision-1201933381/|title=Jeff Daniels Believes Dylan Farrow But Says Turning Down Woody Allen Would be a 'Difficult Decision'|website=[[Indiewire.com]]|first=Zack|last=Sharf|date=February 27, 2018|accessdate=March 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.com/movies/jeff-daniels-woody-allens-legacy-big-asterisk-would-consider-working-with-him/|title=Jeff Daniels Says Woody Allen's Legacy Now Has a 'Big Asterisk'|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|first=Mike|last=Miller|date=March 9, 2018|accessdate=March 10, 2018}}</ref> In February 2018, Savanah Lyon, a theater major at the [[University of California, San Diego]], began organising an online petition to have a course teaching Allen's films removed from the UCSD syllabus. Lyon stated that because of the abuse allegations against him, the university should not have a class devoted to studying Allen's work. On February 16, the UCSD Academic Senate announced that they were going to retain the course on Allen's work, stating that the removal of courses featuring \"controversial material, or even material widely regarded as morally problematic\" would undermine the values of free inquiry and [[academic freedom]].<ref>Flaherty, Collen.(February 26th, 2018.[https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/02/26/uc-san-diego-academic-senate-rejects-student-led-push-cut-course-woody-allen \"Woody Allen and Academic Freedom\"]. Retrieved 3 April 2018.</ref> [[Cate Blanchett]], when asked about the allegations against Allen by [[Christiane Amanpour]], replied \"At the time, I said it\u2019s a very painful and complicated situation for the family, which I hope they have the ability to resolve.\" Blanchett added: \"If these allegations need to be re-examined which, in my understanding, they\u2019ve been through court, then I\u2019m a big believer in the justice system and setting legal precedents,....If the case needs to be reopened, I am absolutely, wholeheartedly in support of that.\"<ref>Telegraph Reporters, (22 March 2018).[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2018/03/23/cate-blanchett-denies-staying-silent-metoo-working-woody-allen/ \"Cate Blanchett denies 'staying silent' on #MeToo while working with Woody Allen\".] ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''. Retrieved 3 April 2018.</ref> [[Javier Bardem]] stated: \"I am very shocked by this sudden treatment. Judgements in the states of New York and Connecticut found him innocent. The legal situation today is the same as in 2007. If there was evidence Woody Allen was guilty, then yes, I would have stopped working with him, but I have doubts.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/apr/19/javier-bardem-defends-woody-allen-i-am-very-shocked-by-this-treatment|title=Javier Bardem defends Woody Allen: 'I am very shocked by this treatment'|website=[[The Guardian]]|first=Guardian|last=Staff|date=April 19, 2018|accessdate=November 9, 2018}}</ref> Bardem in another interview stated: \"\u201cIf the legal situation ever changes [regarding Allen], then I\u2019d change my mind. But for now I don\u2019t agree with the public lynching that he\u2019s been receiving, and if Woody Allen called me to work with him again, I\u2019d be there tomorrow morning. He\u2019s a genius.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/10/javier-bardem-woody-allen-opinion|title=Javier Bardem Calls Woody Allen Backlash a \"Public Lynching\"|website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|first=Yohanna|last=Desta|date=October 19, 2018|accessdate=November 9, 2018}}</ref> [[Alan Alda]] stated \"I'd work with him again if he wanted me. I'm not qualified to judge him. I don't know all the facts. I don't know if he's guilty or innocent. But you can be uncertain \u2014 that's what I go on. I just don't have enough information to convince me I shouldn't work with him. And he's an enormously talented guy.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/alan-alda-mash-legacy-why-hed-work-woody-allen-again-1178289|title=Alan Alda on 'M*A*S*H' Legacy and Why He'd Work With Woody Allen Again|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Benjamin|last=Svetkey|date=January 25, 2019|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}</ref> [[Michael Caine]], who initially expressed regret for working with Allen and said he would never work with him again, later stated: \"If he had a trial and someone proved he had done something, I wouldn\u2019t do it. No. But I didn\u2019t read of him being on trial and being found guilty or fined or sent to prison or anything. This is all things that people say. You can\u2019t go on hearsay the whole time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/global/michael-caine-woody-allen-1202723613/|title=Michael Caine: I Won't Work With Woody Allen Again|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Leo|last=Barraclough|date=March 11, 2018|accessdate=March 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/michael-caine-interview-winston-churchill-jack-nicholson-beatles-778058/|title=The Last Word: Michael Caine on the First Time He Got High and the Role He Regrets Most|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|first=David|last=Browne|date=January 22, 2019|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref> [[Jeff Goldblum]] stated \"I think there is a presumption of innocence until proven guilty, I also admire his body of work. So I would consider working with him again, until I learned something more.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/11/08/jeff-goldblum-says-would-consider-working-with-woody-allen-again/|title=Jeff Goldblum said he would consider working with Woody Allen again, and the Internet is not okay|website=[[The Washington Post]]|first=Allyson|last=Chiu|date=November 8, 2019|accessdate=November 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMoses Farrow wrote an extensive blog post accusing Mia Farrow of emotionally abusing her children and driving some to suicide: \"Most media sources claim my sister Tam died of 'heart failure' at the age of 21. In fact, Tam struggled with depression for much of her life, a situation exacerbated by my mother refusing to get her help, insisting that Tam was just 'moody.' One afternoon in 2000, after one final fight with Mia, which ended with my mother leaving the house, Tam committed suicide by overdosing on pills.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.mamamia.com.au/moses-mia-farrow-children-woody-allen/|title='There was a darkness within our family.' The complex and tragic story of Mia Farrow's 14 children|first=Clare|last=Stephens|publisher=[[Mamamia (website)|Mamamia]]|location=Australia|date=May 28, 2018|accessdate=June 9, 2018|archivedate=May 28, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180528141514/https://www.mamamia.com.au/moses-mia-farrow-children-woody-allen/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=MosesFarrowMay2018 /> His sister Soon-Yi had written similarly in 1992, saying in a statement, \"Mia was always very hot-tempered and given to rages which terrified all the kids. They can't speak freely because they're still dependent on her. But they could really tell stories and I'm sure one day will. It's true Mia was violent with me and I have conclusive proof, but I hope she and Woody can somehow head off a custody trial.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/soon-yi-speaks-lets-not-get-hysterical-197958| title=Soon-Yi Speaks: 'Let's Not Get Hysterical'|work=[[Newsweek]]|date=August 30, 1992|accessdate=June 9, 2018| archivedate=April 13, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413120034/http://www.newsweek.com/soon-yi-speaks-lets-not-get-hysterical-197958|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Woody Allen memoirs \"Apropos of nothing.\" ===\nIn his memoir, Woody Allen addresses Dylan's allegation of abuse. He explains that, unlike other cases of sexual abuse or harassment that could have been ignored without being taken seriously or adequately investigated, Mia Farrow's accusation against him was taken with the utmost seriousness and was immediately and thoroughly investigated by two groups of different experts.\n\nOn the one hand, the police and the prosecution hired the most prestigious experts in the country: the Child Sexual Abuse Clinic at the Yale-New Haven Hospital, whom the police used to look into such matters and who concluded that the evidence conclusively proved that there was not sexual abuse, that Dylan\u00b4s statements had \"a rehearsed quality\" and were likely \"coached or influenced by her mother. \" Regarding the criticism against Yale New haven for having destroyed the original notes at the time of incorporating them into the report, Allen reveals that in the course of the trial it turned out that it was the usual procedure of both Yale New Haven and the FBI to preserve privacy\n\nOn the other hand, the New York State Child Welfare scrupulously investigated the case for 14 months and concluded that there was no credible evidence of abuse and that the allegation was unfounded.\n\nAllen recounts a session of the Yale-New Haven investigation during which Mia Farrow explained to experts how Dylan was so disturbed by the sexual abuse that she immediately rushed to her sister Lark's room for comfort. Farrow described how Dylan hugged Lark and how Lark comforted her. When Allen noted that Lark was in New York on the day the abuse was alleged to have happened and there was no way Dylan would have come to her, hugged her, and Lark comfort her, Mia Farrow changed her account and said that \"\" Lark was in New York at the time, but Dylan hugged her spiritually. \" Allen concluded that while Mia Farrow's story may have had some impact on the judges, it did not mislead investigators.\n\nRegarding the investigation conducted by Connecticut prosecutor Frank Maco, Allen indicates that from the moment the experts the prosecution had hired totally rejected the possibility of sexual abuse, the prosecution's investigation should have been closed. That it was kept open without any justification and that this fact was in favor of Farrow during the custody trial, that the statement at the prosecutor's press conference saying that there was probable cause was totally unfounded once the prosecution experts had already completely ruled out the possibility of sexual abuse. Allen points out that it is absurd to think that the prosecutor did not initiate prosecution becouse he did not want to hurt Dylanl when he had police question Dylan for months without caring at all about Dylan's well-being. Allen also indicates that a nanny and a housekeeper who worked at Mia Farrow's house stated that on multiple occasions the prosecutor \u00a0showed up by the house and he and Mia Farrow went out to luch. Allen \u00a0regrets that this does not seem the most appropriate way conducting an impartial investigation.\n\nAllan also says that in the custody trial, the Court Clerk drove Mia Farrow to her home from the courthose many nigths and thinks it was a \u00a0\u201cunfair conduit to the judge\u201d, recalls the testimony by Moses Farrow, who said he witnessed how Mia Farrow coached Dylan to say that she had been abused, collects the testimony of a babysitter to whom Dylan said \"Mummy want me to lie.\" Allen says that long before the allegation of abuse emerged Mia Farrow took Dylan to a child therapist because the girl had trouble distinguishing between reality and fantasy. The girl who under normal conditions had trouble distinguishing reality from fantasy was at the exclusive care of her mother during a strong and confusing emotional crisis Farrow suggested the child that she had been abused, which ended up leading to Dylan sincerely believed it.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Allen, Woody.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1147948052|title=Apropos of Nothing|isbn=978-1-951627-34-8|oclc=1147948052}}</ref>\n\n\n\n<br />\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|26em}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite news|last1=Hoban|first1=Phoebe|title=Woody and Mia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3uQCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA40|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=September 21, 1992|pages=32\u201342}}\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/04/nyregion/doctor-cites-inconsistencies-in-dylan-farrow-s-statements.html Doctor Cites Inconsistencies In Dylan Farrow's Statements], The New York Times, May 4, 1993\n* [http://articles.latimes.com/1993-02-02/news/mn-952_1_woody-allen Nanny Casts Doubt on Farrow Charges : Custody: She tells Allen's lawyers the actress pressured her to support molestation accusations against him. She says others have reservations], Los Angeles Times, February 2, 1993\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/26/nyregion/agency-drops-abuse-inquiry-in-allen-case.html Agency Drops Abuse Inquiry in Allen Case], The New York Times, October 26, 1993\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Allen, Woody}}\n[[Category:1990s in the United States]]\n[[Category:Entertainment scandals]]\n[[Category:Sexual misconduct allegations]]\n[[Category:Woody Allen]]\n", "name_user": "Tais de Atenas", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDecision", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Woody_Allen_sexual_assault_allegation"}
